deck_excerpt: Can't use the Link-1, so gotta make do
deck_description:
There are just so many things that are wrong with Genex. From the reliance on Genex Controller as their only Tuner monster and the required Tuner for their Synchros for so long, to the Normal Summon-reliance of so many of their Main Deck monsters, to the baffling focus on monster Attributes for their effects and Synchro Materials for so long, to the seemingly random effects plastered on most of their monsters including most of their Synchro monsters. With the initial release of Genex in Duel Terminal, the archetype got an additional wave of support in the Genex Ally monsters which did nothing save for the Synchros that were introduced then, and then they got another wave of support in the R-Genex monsters which were good for what they were, but not good enough to save the already-failing archetype. It wasn’t until the recent Battles of Legend: Terminal Revenge that they were actually playable as a Deck, soon as they got an archetypal Ultimate Offering in Repaired Genex Controller which allowed you to perform an additional Normal Summon of a Genex monster each time one was added to your hand once per chain which came at the cost of locking you into Synchro Summoning using a Genex Tuner as material from the Extra Deck. Now, it is almost apparent that there is an issue here. You can’t play Repaired Genex Controller and go hog wild with its effect in a Deck where you need to do plays involving Summoning monsters from your Extra Deck that are not Synchro Monsters made with a Genex Tuner. This brings us to today’s topic of Genex Prediction Princess. Genex has 1 Level 9 monster in Locomotion R-Genex. Locomotion R-Genex is a Level 9 DARK Machine Synchro Monster that requires a Genex Tuner monster and 1 or more non-Tuner DARK monsters as material. And when it is Synchro Summoned, you take control of the face-up monster your opponent controls with the highest Level. You can’t actually do modern Genex plays in a non-pure Genex Deck, especially not a Deck containing Ritual Monsters and one that must Xyz Summon. So, to get to Locomotion, we need to find ourselves the best Genex Tuner monsters to work with first. That gives us 3 options: Genex Controller, Genex Ally Birdman, and R-Genex Turing. Genex Controller is good because it is accessible off of cards like Unexpected Dai as well as the new Primoredial Tremors. Turing can treat itself as a Level 1 or 3 monster when used for the Synchro Summon of a Genex Synchro Monster with it already being a Level 2 monster. And Birdman can Special Summon itself from your hand by returning a face-up monster you control to the hand. The Level these monsters share is Level 3, so we need to find some Level 6 DARK monsters to Synchro with them into Locomotion. Regarding Turing being a Level 2 monster and also able to treat itself as a Level 1, I did try to work with the Level 7 Allure Queen monsters in Allure Queen LV7 and the new Chaotic Allure Queen, both of which can be searched off of the new Allure Dance which also can send another Spell/Trap you control to the GY to Soul Charge for any number of Allure Queen monsters from GY. But it prevented me from playing Controller which resulted in me having to hard-draw Turing, but I already needed to hard-draw Monstrosity. So, it is a bit awkward having to hard-draw 2 very specific cards. And it also required me having to play a larger number of LIGHT and DARK monsters as Chaotic Allure Queen cannot equip another copy of itself from GY since that would not allow you to get LV7 from Deck as its name needs to be changed as it changes its name to the equipped monster’s name (so if it equips itself, its name doesn’t change). So, the Level 6 DARK monsters I ended on were the Bystial monsters as they are able to set themselves up given you have access to Lubellion. Knowing this, I did not play Birdman and just opted to play Controller and Turing. So, our opening requires The Bystial Lubellion, access to a Genex Tuner which we will imagine as Primoredial Tremors, and Monstrosity. Lubellion sends itself from hand to GY to search for Bystial Magnamhut. Activate Tremors paying 2000 LP and declaring the name of Genex Controller to Special Summon it from Deck. Banish Lubellion from GY to Summon Magnamhut from hand who activates to search a Dragon during the End Phase (which going to be another Bystial for interruption). Synchro Controller and Magnamhut into Locomotion and then target it with Monstrosity to get Bibliomuse and Deus-X from Deck. And from there, just make Aggregator, sending Herald for full Prediction Princess combo. So, in addition to our normal Prediction Princess endboard, we also have a Bystial searched during the End Phase and Tremors in GY which I will explain later. It’s not the best thing, but we are experimenting here and you gotta do what you gotta do.

For the monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei is a Quick Effect to flip a monster face-up or face-down and during the End Phase, she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down. Tarotreith can either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei’s End Phase effect. On flip, she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters either face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back from GY face-down if she was tributed and sent there. On flip, she can add a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand, and while she’s face-up on field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s effects. 2 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute than it from Deck. 2 Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag which can Special Summon itself from your hand if there is a monster in the EMZ and it is a Level 9. 3 The Bystial Lubellion and 1 each of Bystial Magnamhut, Bystial Druiswurm, and Bystial Baldrake. Lubellion can send itself from hand to GY to search for a Bystial monster except itself. Magnamhut adds a Dragon monster from Deck or GY to your hand during the End Phase with this effect activating on Special Summon. Druiswurm targets a Special Summoned monster your opponent controls and sends it to the GY if it is sent from the field to the GY. Baldrake can Tribute another LIGHT or DARK monster when your opponent Special Summons a Ritual, Fusion, Synchro, Xyz, and/or Link Monster and target 1 of those Special Summoned monsters to banish it. All of the Level 6 Bystials can banish a LIGHT or DARK monster from either GY to Special Summon themselves from hand with this effect being a Quick Effect if your opponent controls a monster. 3 R-Genex Turing and 1 Genex Controller. Turing can Quick Effect Special Summon itself from your hand and immediately Synchro Summon a Genex Synchro Monster and while it is on the field, it can also be treated as a Level 1 or 3 monster when used for the Synchro Summon of a Genex Synchro Monster. Genex Controller is a Level 3 Normal Tuner Monster which we are playing for Primoredial Tremors.

Spell/Traps: 3 Pot of Prosperity. 3 Primoredial Tremors. This card pays 2000 LP and has you declare the name of a Normal Monster. If you control no monsters, you can Special Summon the Normal Monster whose name you declared from your Deck and Normal Monsters with the declared name and Primoredial monsters cannot be destroyed by battle until the end of your opponent’s turn. This effect makes the card basically Unexpected Dai, but we also need to consider its GY effect. If your opponent Normal Summons a monster, you can banish this card from your GY and target a Normal Monster you control or n your GY to banish 1 monster on the field with lower ATK. With Controller being our Normal Monster in this Deck, this can banish a monster with less than 1400 ATK which is actually pretty good considering you can get rid of your opponent’s Normal Summon or another monster they control. 3 Pre-Preparation of Rites which searches a Ritual Spell from Deck and a Ritual Monster from Deck or GY whose name is mentioned on that card. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down. 2 Prediction Ritual which can only Ritual Summon Prediction Princess Tarotrei, and you can banish it from GY except the turn it was sent there to search for a Prediction Princess monster. 1 Chaos Space which sends a LIGHT or DARK monster from hand to GY to add a LIGHT or DARK monster that cannot be Normal Summoned/Set from your Deck to your hand whose Level is between 4 to 8 and you can banish it from GY to target a banished LIGHT or DARK monster that cannot be Normal Summoned/Set and place it on the bottom of your Deck to draw 1 card. 1 Instant Fusion for Master of Ham. And 3 World Legacy Monstrosity which either Special Summons a Level 9 from hand or targets a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from Deck with a different Type and Attribute than that monster but with different names.

Extra Deck: 1 Master of Ham which can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or Deck face-down on Fusion Summon. 1 Arms of Genex Return Zero which needs a DARK Tuner and 1 or more non-Tuner monsters. When your opponent activates a monster effect, you can Quick Effect banish a monster with the same Attribute from your GY to negate the activation and destroy that monster. And you can only banish each Attribute once per turn to activate this effect. You can also target up to 6 Genex monsters with different Attributes that are banished and/or in your GY to shuffle them into the Deck and destroy that many cards in the Spell/Trap Zones. 1 Locomotion R-Genex. 1 Cloudcastle as an alternative Level 9 Synchro to go into. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which searches a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from Deck if it is sent to GY. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder. 2 Mereologic Aggregator which can send a monster from your Extra Deck to GY on Xyz Summon and it can target monsters in your GY up to the number of materials attached to it to detach the same number of materials and attach the monsters you targeted in GY to itself in exchange. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 S:P Little Knight and 1 I:P Masquerena. 1 Repair Genex Controller which we can potentially make to turn on Turing to go into Return Zero on our opponent’s turn and 1 Gravity Controller.

Side Deck: 3 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 2 Thunder King, the Lightningstrike Kaiju, 3 Kashtira Fenrir, 1 Harpie’s Feather Duster, 3 Dark Ruler No More, and 3 Evenly Matched.

deck_excerpt: My tribute to Shannon Long. Here to punish players that don't play around columns and refuse to read.
deck_description: Back during TOSS format, the PPG success of Shannon Long with this unconventional strategy that plays the game on a strange axis resonated with me. I played this deck at locals, to some tops, and regionals, unfortunatley with none. Mind you, this was pre-Girsu and pre-Lib, so there's more explosivity in the combos. While the deck hasn't changed much since 2020, I'm doing alright with it on the Master Duel ladder, taking advantage of button-clickers and non-readers left and right. You'll still brick to high heaven about 20% of the time, but such is life. Girsu does give the deck some plays going first, but the goal is still blinding second, using Gameciel and Girsu's token summoning effect to create columns, or resorting to board breakers you can set and activate on the same turn, or normal summoning a hand trap and converting into Anima or Almiraj. I'm maining copies of all three column floodgates, mainly due to a lack of a side deck, just for matchups where Whisper's Spell negation comes in handy.

deck_name: The Ultimate Lair of Darkness deck (heavy control)
deck_description:
Main Engine (13 cards)

  • 1x Darkest Diabolos, Lord of the Lair
  • 3x Lilith, Lady of Lament
  • 3x Ahrima, the Wicked Warden
  • 3x Lair of Darkness
  • 3x Skill Drain

These cards form the core of the deck, allowing you to maximize the potential of Lair of Darkness. With Skill Drain on the field, you can tribute your opponent's monsters as cost, which is incredibly powerful.

Bystial Engine (8 cards)

  • 3x Bystial Lubellion
  • 1x Bystial Druiswurm
  • 1x Bystial Magnamhut
  • 1x Bystial Saronir
  • 1x Bystial Baldrake
  • 1x Branded Regained

This small Bystial engine provides additional damage and board presence. Most Bystial monsters activate from the hand or graveyard, effectively bypassing Skill Drain's restriction. While Branded Regained’s search is affected by Skill Drain, it remains a valuable resource.

Support Cards

  • 2x Nibiru, the Primal Being - Excellent for board wipes.
  • 3x Lord of the Heavenly Prison - All its effects bypass Skill Drain, providing protection and utility.

Draw Power (3 cards)

  • 3x Pot of Extravagance

Since you won't rely on your Extra Deck heavily, Pot of Extravagance offers consistent draw power. Additionally, it can be searched by Lord of the Heavenly Prison.

Extra Deck-Related Cards

  • 3x Dogmatika Punishment - Use with respective Extra Deck targets.

Additional Tech Cards

  • 2x Metaverse - Enhances Lair of Darkness consistency.
  • 2x Ice Dragon's Prison - Effective for banishing key graveyard targets and non-targetable monsters.
  • 2x Destructive Daruma Cannon - Useful for removing Link Monsters or disrupting the opponent’s turn.
  • 2x Back to the Front - Recurs Lilith or other key monsters.

Extra Deck Targets

  • Chimeraking Overdragon - Revives Lilith.
  • Garura, Wings of Resonant Life - Provides draw power.
  • Elder Entity N'tss - Clears backrow or strong monsters.
  • Number C107: Neo Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon Dragon - Deals with larger threats and sends a Beast/Winged-Beast to the graveyard afterward.
  • Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder and Starliege Seyfert - Situational options.

deck_excerpt: A basic deck primarily based around the Dark Magician Girl.
deck_description: A deck that is simple and sweet just like the Dark Magician Girl.
(low cost deck) Banishing monster to summon nemleria

Main: The main deck has the usual standard ratio's of the Millennium monsters except I added 3 monsters that I feel do help support the deck. Maiden of the Millennium Moon is a LV 4 monster that gives The Unstoppable Exodia Incarnate target protection for the turn, which is great during a format where player are running Effect Veiler and Infinite Impermenence. The second card is Exodius The Ultimate Forbidden Lord. This card of course is being tested. The reason for this card is for the late game when you have already summoned all your Exodia Incarnates and Super Polymerization targets. You can Special summon Exodius from your hand by recycling all monsters that are currently in the GY back to your main deck and or extra deck. This deck really needs to play the Exodia fusion monster in order to win games as fast as possible as well as recycling your Super Poly targets to re-summon them again if need be. Also who doesnt want to re-use their hand traps again. Ghost Sister And Spooky Dogwood is a very good card in this deck and it really isnt to win in time only. The Exodia fusion can take advantage of the Life Point gain since its attack becomes the same as your LP during Damage Calculation when it battles.

Extra: What I decided to do with the extra is not make it to complicated. Super poly targets are the usual suspects but i decided to include Yubel The Loving Defender Forever since Yubel is really tough to beat in this current format for this deck especially. There are 2 cool ways to make S:P Little Knight in this deck. When going second you can summon the LV 1 pieces of Exodia and summon Relinquished Anima Steal a monster and use Anima and any other Millennium monster to make her. The going first way is to summon a piece but link into Artemis, The Magistus Moon Maiden since all the Exodia pieces are spellcasters. I noticed that this deck doesnt do so well with floodgates like Skill Drain so i added  Donner, Dagger Fur Hire to take care of those situational cards since her effect is a cost and bypasses Skill Drain. All your monsters in the main deck are all different types so you can summon it. Black Luster Soldier-Soldier Of Chaos (BLS) is a really good link monster since you do play alot of high LV monsters. Using Sengenjin Wake From A Millennium or Exodius, BLS cant be targeted or destroyed by card effects. He can deal with cards that cant die by battle by banishing them, get more attack in case something is to strong on the field, or help to win a game by attacking twice the next turn. I added Linguriboh only because my locals have been using Knightmare Iblee lately, but you can play anything else in this spot.

Side: I decided to make my side deck for going first since most of the time you want to go second and break a board. Of course there are other cards I want to test for going first that arent handtraps. Sauravis,The Ancient And Ascended is for targeting protection, and Eye Of Illusion which have 3 effects that are great in this deck. I might change my side deck to include these after we get a banlist but for now handtraps with Crossout Designator is doing fine for me. You can take out the 1 Maiden and 2 Exodius to main Impermenence and add Nibiru The Primal Being to the side deck.

Final Thoughts: I hope you read the explanations and it helped you. I cannot wait for the Blue-Eyes Of The Heart Millennium support we are getting in Rage of the Abyss (ROTA) and start testing. I always update my decks when banlist and formats change so stay tuned for that.

deck_excerpt: Set up Lo + Skull Guardian... THEN WIN!
deck_description:
Voiceless Voice is the incredible new ritual archetype coming out in the selection pack "Wings of the Guardian" in Masterduel! The archetype really takes the ladder by storm, since it is incredibly consistent, can play very well into Maxx "C," and takes advantage of the plethora of ritual support that has come out the last decade!

The simplistic strategy of setting up a singular towers omni-negate in the form of Skull Guardian, Protector, supported by his friends Lo, Sauravis, Saffira and various continuous backrow spells/traps is surprisingly solid in the cutthroat competitive meta of Masterduel!

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
 
ARCHETYPES, ENGINES AND DECKBUILDING
 
The deck is primarily composed of VOICELESS VOICE cards. A small Dogmatika engine is used for additional utility and consistency. 
 
The VOICELESS VOICE cards turbo out Lo, her protector and your best boss monster, Skull Guardian. Lo, Diviner of the Herald, Pre-Preparation of Rites, Barrier of the Voiceless Voice and Saffira Dragon Queen are all maxxed out at 3, since they are starters for the deck. All these cards start up the Voiceless Voice strategy by themselves, and can act as extenders if you have other combo pieces in your hand. A singular One for One is used since it summons Lo, and Lo is a one card starter. Blessing of the Voiceless, Radiance of the Voiceless, Sauravis Dragon Sage, Sauravis are all played at 1 since they are powerful, but not starters - they are all searchable as you combo. Prayers of the Voiceless are played at 2, because it's the deck's archetypal ritual spell, enables floating for your Ritual monsters, enables a longer grind game. 
 
A small DOGMATIKA engine is used primarily to summon Dogmatika Maximus. Maximus is able to send to the GY Herald of the Arc Light, which searches for your Voiceless Voice combo pieces. Nadir Servant also doubles as a board breaker since it can send to GY N'tss to destroy a card on your opponent's field. 
 
The STAPLES featured in this deck are the usual suspects in Masterduel - the 12 card "Maxx C" package (3 Ash, 3 Maxx, 2 Called By, 1 Crossout and 2 Gamma + 1 Driver) so that you can come out on top of the "Maxx C Minigame." 1 Imperm and 1 Droll are popular staples and Crossout targets to negate. A single Pot of Extravagance and Pot of Prosperity for more card advantage and consistency are used since the Extra Deck is not needed much and can be banished without much consequence. 
 
45 cards are used in this strategy because it has so many garnets in it that are searched as part of it's main combo. 44 cards means that there is less chance you'd draw into your garnets like Radiance of the Voiceless, Dogmatika Maximus and Psy-Frame Driver, and more chance you'll draw into starters and staples!
 
COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN
 
The Voiceless Voice archetype is a relatively simple and linear strategy. It mainly turbos out Lo along with Skull Guardian for it's omni-negate and destroy. The rest of the cards basically support the strategy to get to that desired board, or offer layers of protection/floating to Lo and Skull Guardian.  
 
Here is the optimal combo for Voiceless Voice: 
 
Lo, The Prayers of the Voiceless Voice = Skull Guardian, Protector (omni-negate destroy) + Sauravis (targeting protection) + Radiance of the Voiceless (target destroy of at least 1 of your opponent's cards) + Prayers of the Voiceless in GY (allows your Ritual monster to float to another form deck) + Barrier of the Voiceless (follow-up and protection)
  1. Normal summon Lo. Search for Barrier of the Voiceless Voice. 
  2. Activate Barrier. Activate Barrier's effect to search for Saffira, Dragon Queen of the Voiceless Voice. 
  3. Activate Saffira, Dragon Queen to send to the GY Prayers of the Voiceless Voice and add to hand Skull Guardian, Protector of the Voiceless Voice. 
  4. Activate Saffira's effect in the GY to ritual summon Skull Guardian from hand by tributing Lo in the field. 
  5. CL1 activate Lo's effect in the GY to summon herself from GY, CL2 activate Skull Guardian's effect to add another Voiceless Voice monster from deck (either Saffira or Lo for follow-up, Sauravis, Dragon Sage for another interruption, or OG Sauravis for targeting protection).
  6. Link away Skull Guardian and Lo to link summon Dyna Mondo. (This is optional, the goal of this is to summon Lo again in your opponent's turn so she can place another Voiceless continuous spell/trap on the field. Beware, this is risky, if Dyna Mondo somehow gets negated by Called By or something you're relatively defenseless).
  7. During your opponent's draw phase, tribute Dyna Mondo to summon Skull Guardian from the GY. 
  8. Lo's trigger effect in the GY activates to summon herself since Skull Guardian was summoned. Lo places Radiance of the Voiceless Voice on the field. (If you already have Radiance, place Blessing of the Voiceless Voice). 
This is the main combo for Voiceless Voice. Unlike other strategies, this deck doesn't really have nuances or different combo routes, it is very linear and does the same thing. Simplicity is good though, since Voiceless reaches it's goal extremely proficiently - that is summoning Lo with her protector, Skull Guardian. Even if your combo gets interrupted, the other starters in your hand can also be extenders!
 
GOING FIRST, Voiceless Voice is extremely consistent and easily sets up a singular omni-negate/destroy coupled with a robust resource loop. Your opponent would generally be hard-pressed to breakthrough the defensive control strategy that Voiceless establishes. If your opponent finds themselves unable to play with your interruption, the Voiceless Voice duelist would quickly out-resource them and beatdown their monsters and lifepoints for the win. 
 
GOING SECOND, Voiceless Voice has a hard time playing into established boards. The good news is that Voiceless is so consistent that it can jam a lot of staples into the maindeck, so handtraps are the best way to enable Voiceless to go second. You can also bait out interruption with the many starters this deck has, and once your opponent runs out of actions, you can go full combo! 
 
GENERAL TIPS
  • Voiceless Voice has a lot of redundant starters and extenders. You mostly only need one starter to go through for you to go full combo. Try to bait out your opponent's handtraps/interruption!
  • To start off, try to search out Sauravis first if you don't have it already. This deck's signature monster's targeting protection actually hard counters common interruptions like Effect Veiler and Impermanence!
  • Voiceless Voice does many of it's actions without a monster on the field. This means that Psy-Frame Gear Gamma is almost always live to counter your opponent's monster effects!
  • Making Dyna Mondo may eventually get you another backrow Voiceless Voice spell/trap on the field, but be careful - it's risky! Your opponent may Called By the Grave or or Ghost Belle it and you may be just dead from that point on!
  • Droll and Lockbird really kills this deck. To play around it, search for your most important combo piece first so you can at least put something on the board after the Droll resolves.
  • Your opponent may remove Protector of the Voiceless from the field, but their archetypal ritual spell, Prayers of the Voiceless Voice allows your ritual monsters to float! If your opponent doesn't remove this card from the GY as well, your board is still extremely powerful since your monster just comes back!
  • Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!
CONCLUDING COMMENTARY
 
It's really cool that the folks in the Yugioh offices are redesigning ancient cards from the beginning of Yugioh into competent, competitive flavourful archetypes! First it was Thunder Dragon, then Yubel, and now Voiceless Voice! Lo and her friends has certainly experienced quite the glow-up compared to their early days when they were released! I wonder what gets retrained next? The Mask guys from the first set of Yugioh? Will Jinzo become competitively viable? Only time will tell!
 
GLHF Duelists!
Did someone say Dark Hole?

deck_name: Zombie P.U.N.K once Beatrice is Banned
deck_excerpt: Fun Combo deck with a bit of luck involved :)
deck_description:
With the new fiend smith engine practically garunteeing Beatrice's ban I thought it would be a good idea to make an update to my favorite pet deck and prepare for the inevitable.

For the uninitiated, this deck revolves around using the P.U.N.K engine to mill a ton of zombies into the grave and then beat your opponent through the grind game or savy link/synchro plays. The one card combo is Ze-Amin or Emergency teleport, we use it and follow a shortened P.U.N.K line until you land on Jam Dragon, Ze-Amin, and Psychic tracker. from there you make Immortal dragon and send ghost sleeper to grave and grab ghost fusion. Next you use ghost fusion to make garura using immortal dragon and Changshi Spiridao, banishing Changshi. Changs effect will allow you to banish immortal or a zombie you discarded for the punks and then you dump mezuki off changshi. This leaves you with two level six monsters and the ability to mezuki for foxy tune (provided you have zombie world) or any of the other level 8's in the deck. This let's you make Pilgrim Reaper to mill 5 and The Zombie Vampire to mill 4 and special summon. From that position the world is your oister. You usually want to dump garura for the draw and if you're playing with the tearlaments package (more on that later) it can set you up for dragstapelia, though it is worth noting that changshi doesn't get shuffled back into the deck when sent as XYZ material.

Talking numbers, it may seem odd to run multiple copies of balerdroc, zombie world, and necroworld banshee, but from my experience it helps protect yourself against bystials or having your zombie world destroyed. If you hard open them, as long as you have Ze-Amin you can just discard them for cost and be in the clear. 

The extra deck I made has cards I personally like using in this strategy for some unique forms of interaction, but I have also included more generic/ out there options in the side deck. My favorite interaction chain is using Zombie Dragon Lord to revive the Yuki-onna link 3 to have an on summon negate and then using her (once she bites the dust) to summon Skeletal Felgrand dragon for a banish and maybe a monster negate if it comes up. 

The side deck has a lot of interesting cards in it. The tear engine are kinda iffy as the deck isn't really built for drawing them (except sheiren), but they can be used to make dragstapelia if you want another monster negate. Necro dragon and Dragnecro are both fun cards that you can mess around with in a more casual enviornment, especially Necro dragon as it can get really big. There is the option of making Draglubion instead of the zombie vampire or making it later and going into number 92, but I'm not the biggest fan of this line. Zealantis is nice for triggering the on summon effects of yuki-onna 3 or Skeletal Felgrand on your turn and otking your opponent once you're done sitting on Yuki-onna link 4. Small World is a card I would highly consider running in the deck as an extra piece of consistancy. There's plenty of ways to bridge to Ze-Amin using it in the deck, but it has a hefty cost.

Overall, this is a much weaker version of the beatrice deck, but also a more fun one in my opinion. It has lots of fun interaction on your opponents turn and it's always a good time milling 1/4th of your deck in two moves. The only downside is that it is a one card combo deck and if that one card gets stopped then you can't really play, but even with that issue it's still my favorite deck by a country mile. Of course the fiend smith engine would help this deck a lot, but it's pretty expensive (ironic coming from the guy that put S:P into the main) and I wanted to build something more affordable than that.

Thanks for reading.

deck_description:
Yu-Gi-Oh! Booster Pack Vol. 1 (também conhecido como Booster 1) foi lançado em 4 de Fevereiro de 1999 como um dos primeiros pacotes de reforço no Yu-Gi-Oh! Official Card Game. Ele precedeu apenas o Vol.1, que foi lançado no mês anterior. Aqui estão alguns detalhes sobre ele:

  • Layout do Cartão: Como todos os conjuntos da Série 1, os cartões do Booster 1 usavam o layout do cartão da Série 1. Esse layout é distinguido dos layouts posteriores pela falta de um Número do Cartão sob a arte do cartão e pelo Holograma do Olho de Anúbis em seu canto inferior direito.
  • Distribuição: Os cartões do Booster 1 foram distribuídos por meio de máquinas de venda Carddass.
  • Tipos de Cartão: O conjunto contém 40 cartões, incluindo 33 Cartas de Monstro Normais, 2 Cartas de Magia Normais e 5 Cartas de Magia de Equipamento.
  • Novas Introduções: O Booster 1 introduziu duas cartas, “Blue Medicine” e “Raimei”, no universo Yu-Gi-Oh! As outras 38 cartas já haviam aparecido no mangá, anime, videogames ou outros produtos da vida real.
  • Reimpressões: Cinco das cartas deste conjunto foram reimpressas do Vol.1, enquanto as outras 35 cartas foram introduzidas no OCG no Booster 1. Apenas 14 delas foram impressas no Yu-Gi-Oh! Trading Card Game, e 25 nunca foram impressas no TCG.

Se você está interessado em colecionar ou jogar com essas cartas nostálgicas, talvez queira explorar mercados online ou lojas de cartas locais. Aproveite sua aventura Yu-Gi-Oh! 🌟

Deck Inicial: Yugi é um Deck Inicial no Yu-Gi-Oh! Jogo de Cartas Colecionáveis (TCG). Lançados junto com o Deck Inicial: Kaiba, eles são o primeiro e o segundo deck da série de Decks Iniciais do TCG. Também é lançado no Yu-Gi-Oh! Jogo de cartas oficial (OCG) em inglês asiático e coreano.

 

A coleção foi lançada no Yu-Gi-Oh! Trading Card Game (TCG) em três estampas diferentes em inglês - norte-americano, europeu e oceânico - bem como em francês europeu, franco-canadense, alemão, italiano, português e espanhol. Os conjuntos em inglês europeu, francês europeu, alemão e italiano contêm menos cartas do que as outras impressões, cada uma incluindo 46 em vez de 50 cartas.

 

"Caveira Evocada" desta coleção foi anteriormente distribuída em particular como um cartão de amostra, bem como distribuída no WB Kids! "Duelin' Monsters Giveaway" em novembro de 2001. Em ambos os casos, o cartão foi impresso usando papel brilhante como usado para cartões OCG, e o texto do cartão foi quebrado em uma posição diferente; além disso, o cartão de amostra tinha a palavra "SAMPLE" impressa no verso do cartão, enquanto a promoção do sorteio não tinha o Holograma do Olho de Anúbis no canto inferior direito.

CONTEXT: I initially posted this Deck and pasted 4+ pages of text which broke the page (the "Read More" button literally disappeared), so I am posting this in 2 parts to make it shorter and keep things easier to digest and read.

For the Main Deck Monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during your End Phase. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's effect in the End Phase. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-downn and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back face-down after being Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s card effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent's side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute. 1 Pot of the Forbidden which has a Flip Effect that lets you choose between Drawing 2 cards, returning all Spell/Traps on the field to the hand, destroying all monsters your opponent controls, or looking at your opponent's hand and shuffling a card from it back into the Deck. Moving into the Union Monsters, they all have the Union Monster effect that is a soft once per turn effect to either equip them to an appropriate monster you control or unequip them to Special Summon themselves and if the equipped monster would be destroyed, you destroy it instead. 1 Union Driver who can, while equipped to a monster, can banish itself to equip an appropriate Level 4 or lower Union Monster to the monster it was equipped to. This card basically allows you to get around Union Hangar’s restriction of being unable to Special Summon the Union Monster you equipped by its effect. 1 B-Buster Drake which non-opt adds a Union Monster from Deck to hand if sent from the field to the GY. This card is nuts for being able to basically infinitely search for Union Monsters as long as it’s sent from the field to the GY. It doesn’t play a role in the Prediction Princess combo the Deck has, but it is here for the non-Ritual combo. 3 X-Cross Cannon which is not a Union monster. It can Special Summon itself from your hand if you control a LIGHT Machine Fusion or Union Monster and you can equip a LIGHT Machine Union Monster from your Deck to it, being treated as being equipped by that card’s effect at the cost of LIGHT-locking you from the Extra Deck. 1 Y-Dragon Yearhead which on Special Summon, can equip a Level 4 LIGHT Machine monster from hand or GY to it, LIGHT-locking you from the Extra Deck. 2 Z-Zillion Tank which on Special Summon can equip a banished LIGHT Machine monster to itself, LIGHT-locking you from the Extra Deck in doing so. And finally, 1 Torque Tune Gear which is a Level 1 LIGHT Tuner Union Monster. When it is equipped to a monster, that monster becomes a Tuner and gains 500 ATK/DEF. Its Level is really important for making Ib and the other Synchros, but you could use it to get a Level 4 Tuner to go into a Level 8 Synchro, but with us being LIGHT-locked, there aren’t that many great LIGHT Level 8 Synchro Monsters in the game. 

Spell/Traps: 1 World Legacy Monstrosity which either Special Summons a Level 9 monster from hand or targets a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different Type and Attribute but with different names. It is searchable off of Ib, so we just need the 1 copy in the Deck. 1 World Legacy Succession which targets a monster in your GY and Special Summons it to Linkpoint. This is a secondary target in Deck to search off of Ib and it potentially allows you to bring back Hyper Dragon Cannon if you Linked it off. 1 Terraforming. 3 Union Hangar which adds a LIGHT Machine Union monster from Deck on activation and once per turn if a LIGHT Machine Union monster(s) is Normal or Special Summoned to your field, you can target and equip 1 of them with an appropriate LIGHT Machine Union monster with a different name from your Deck but that monster cannot be Special Summoned this turn. 3 Pot of Prosperity. 3 Pre-Preparation of Rites which searches a Ritual Spell from Deck and a Ritual Monster from Deck or GY whose name is mentioned on that card. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down. 2 Prediction Ritual which can only Ritual Summon Prediction Princess Tarotrei, and you can banish it from GY except the turn it was sent there to search for a Prediction Princess monster. 1 Instant Fusion for Master of Ham. 1 Silhouhatte Trick to set off of Rabbit. It Special Summons itself as a Level 4 DARK Illusion Effect Monster with 1500 ATK and 600 DEF and its effect on Special Summon allows you to target face-up cards your opponent controls, up to the number of Illusion monsters you control to negate their effects until the end of the turn which totals to 2 counting both Rabbit and this card. Also, it has the non-battle destruction effect of Illusion Monsters. And finally, 3 Infinite Impermanence. 

Extra Deck: 1 XYZ-Hyper Dragon Cannon. It is the Level 9 monster we are utilizing today. It is a Level 9 LIGHT Machine Fusion Monster that requires X-Cross Cannon, Y-Dragon Yearhead, and Z-Zillion Tank as material, and it must first be Special Summoned from your Extra Deck by banishing those cards from your field and/or GY. As a soft opt during your opponent’s turn, it can quick effect discard a card to target a card your opponent controls and destroy it. And as a non-opt, it can banish itself from field or GY and reveal a Level 8 LIGHT Machine Fusion Monster in your Extra Deck to Special Summon up to 3 of the monsters who are mentioned on it from GY and/or banishment. That second effect is better off being used in actual A-to-Z Union Decks. 1 Union Controller which is a Fusion Monster that requires a LIGHT Machine and either Y-Dragon Yearhead or Z-Zillion Tank and must also first be Special Summoned from your Extra Deck by banishing those cards you control. If it is Special Summoned from your Extra Deck, you can search for a Spell/Trap that mentions “Union monster” in its text. And as a soft opt, you can Special Summon a LIGHT Machine Normal or Union Monster from your hand. This card is crazy as it literally searches Union Hangar and can get a Union monster out even after you’ve already used your Normal Summon. 1 Master of Ham which can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or Deck face-down on Fusion Summon. 1 Chaofeng, Phantom of the Yang Zing. The effect we are using it for is its effect to prevent your opponent from activating monster effects with the same attributes as the Yang Zing monsters used for its Synchro Summon while it is on the field. It is a Level 9 Synchro we can go into with Denglong or we can use it as an alternative Level 9 to go into. During the Ritual combo of the Deck, when you have only Ib and X-Cross Cannon on the field, you can choose to not activate Cannon and Synchro into Chaofeng and activate Monstrosity targeting it. In this case, you are not yet LIGHT-locked and are able to make Mereologic Aggregator sending Herald as we are still playing it anyways. You can choose to cut Herald, Aggregator, and Gravity Controller for cards like Zeus, Nine-Lives Cat, and Gravity Controller if you want to. 1 F.A. Dawn Dragster which once per turn reduces its Level by 2 to negate the activation of your opponent’s Spell/Trap Card or effect and destroy it. 1 Ib the World Chalice Justiciar which searches a World Legacy card from Deck on Synchro Summon. 1 Denglong, First of the Yang Zing which adds a Yang Zing card on Synchro Summon which is the Nine Pillars in the Side Deck. If you feel like having Chaofeng and Nine Pillars on field is better for the match-up, just side Nine Pillars in. 1 Herald of the Arc Light which searches for a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from Deck if sent to the GY. 1 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 Knightmare Gryphon which can discard a card a target a Spell/Trap in your GY on Link Summon to set it, but it cannot be activated this turn, and if it was co-linked on activation, you can draw a card. And while it is on the field, Special Summoned monsters on the field cannot activate their effects unless they are Linked. 1 Platinum Gadget which can Special Summon a Level 4 or lower Machine from your hand to one of its arrows and it cannot be used as Link Material the turn it is Link Summoned which is not a problem as we can banish it for Union Controller. 1 Silhouhatte Rabbit which has the non-battle destruction effect of Illusion monsters and on Link Summon, it can set a Continuous Trap from your Deck that can Special Summon itself as a Monster, but it makes Rabbit unable to be used as Link Material for this turn. And if a card in the Spell/Trap Zone is Special Summoned to the Monster Zone, you can target and destroy an opponent’s Spell/Trap. And finally, 1 Gravity Controller.

Side Deck: 3 Kashtira Fenrir, 1 Called By the Grave, 2 Lightning Storm, 1 Harpie’s Feather Duster, 3 Dark Ruler No More, 3 Evenly Matched, 1 Nine Pillars of the Yang Zing which is a Counter Trap which can negate the activation of a Spell/Trap Card or monster effect while you control a Yang Zing monster and shuffle that card back into the Deck and destroying another Yang Zing card you control, and 1 Angel Statue - Azurune which can be Special Summoned as a LIGHT Level 4 Fairy Effect Monster with 1800 ATK/DEF and when your opponent would Special Summon a monster(s) while it is in the Monster Zone, you can send a Continuous Trap in your Monster Zone that was Special Summoned from the Spell/Trap Zone to the GY to negate the Summon and destroy those monsters.
Let's Chemistry

CONTEXT: I initially posted this Deck and pasted 4+ pages of text which broke the page (the "Read More" button literally disappeared), so I am posting this in 2 parts to make it shorter and keep things easier to digest and read. 

PART 2

The new retrains of the XYZ Union Monsters and XYZ-Dragon Cannon from the LIGHT Duelist set are just so incredibly cool. They are able to facilitate cards like ABC-Dragon Buster, the original XYZ-Dragon Cannon, A-to-Z-Dragon Buster Cannon, as well as their new Fusion boss monster so easily. X-Cross Cannon, the retrain of X-Head Cannon, by itself is practically full combo in most cases for the Deck. I tested what the Deck could do as soon as I saw that their new boss, XYZ-Hyper Dragon Cannon, was a Level 9 monster and I simply just tested the Deck with ABC first. This version of the Deck can put out 2 to 3 copies of Dragon Buster onto the field easily, but it all came at a cost. X-Cross Cannon’s effect to equip a LIGHT Machine Union Monster from Deck to it as well as the on-Summon effects of Y-Dragon Yearhead and Z-Zillion Tank locked you into LIGHT monsters from the Extra Deck. When you put this into context for Prediction Princess, that means that you cannot go into Mereologic Aggregator which is such a powerful card for the Deck as it is a DARK monster. It can send Herald of the Arc Light from Extra Deck to GY for a search and being able to reattach it, getting another search once you Link Aggregator off which is incredible for a Ritual Deck. The thought of forgoing Aggregator put me on a search for a way to not have to use the effects of the new Unions to prevent myself from being LIGHT-locked so that I could access Aggregator. And that became a futile search several times a month. So, I finally decided to move past that and just give up on trying to Summon Aggregator which apparently was the thing holding me back this entire time when it came to making an XYZ Prediction Princess Deck. This version of the Deck that I ended on utilizes Torque Tune Gear to Synchro with any of the Level 4 Unions into Ib the World Chalice Justiciar to have access to World Legacy Monstrosity. We would simply make Ib before activating X-Cross Cannon’s effect to equip from Deck, allowing us to get the materials for XYZ-Hyper Dragon Cannon on field/GY, giving us a Level 9 target on field for Monstrosity which would then get us Prediction Princess Bibliomuse and either Deus-X Krawler or Pot of the Forbidden from Deck. That gives access to Bibliomuse, so as long as we draw access to a Ritual Spell and a Ritual Monster, we have full Prediction Princess combo which does not require us to go into the Extra Deck at that point as we are just Ritual Summoning from there. But the Ib and the remaining Level 9 on field can be used as Link Material for Silhouhatte Rabbit and we are playing a target for it which gives us 2 pieces of interaction alongside Hyper Dragon Cannon for another interaction all in addition to our Prediction Princess plays. But let’s say that we do not draw the Ritual part of our Deck. Well, as I have mentioned, X-Cross Cannon is basically full combo for the Union half of the Deck, so we can just use it to get to Hyper Dragon Cannon as well as have enough material on board to put other forms of interaction onto the field. I’m going to describe the combos for if you have Ritual access as well as if you don’t have Ritual access. 

For full Prediction Princess combo, you need Union Hangar, X-Cross Cannon, and Ritual access, which we will say is Prediction Princess Tarotrei and Prediction Ritual for this example (Pre-Preparation of Rites also works here). Activate Hangar and search for Torque Tune Gear. Normal Summon Tune Gear which triggers Union Hangar to equip Union Driver from Deck to it. Driver effect to banish it to equip Y-Dragon Yearhead from Deck to Tune Gear (you could also equip Z-Zillion Tank instead, just get the remaining one later in the combo). Y-Dragon unequips itself to Special Summon itself. Now that you have a LIGHT Machine Union Monster on field, activate X-Cross Cannon in hand to Special Summon itself. Synchro Tune Gear and Y-Dragon into Ib the World Chalice Justiciar. Ib searches for World Legacy Monstrosity. Activate X-Cross Cannon to equip Z-Zillion Tank to it. Banish X-Cross Cannon, Y-Dragon Yearhead, and Z-Zillion Tank to Special Summon XYZ-Hyper Dragon Cannon from Extra Deck. Activate Monstrosity targeting it for Prediction Princess Bibliomuse and Pot of the Forbidden from Deck. Link Pot and Ib into Silhouhatte Rabbit. Rabbit activates to set Silhouhatte Trick from Deck. Activate Prediction Ritual tributing Bibliomuse to Ritual Summon Tarotrei. Bibliomuse Special Summons herself back from GY face-down. Tarotrei flips Bibliomuse face-up. Bibliomuse activates to search for Prediction Princess Tarotreith and Underworld Ritual of Prediction from Deck. Activate Underworld Ritual tributing Bibliomuse to Ritual Summon Tarotreith face-down. Proceed to End Phase and you could activate Tarotrei to Summon back Pot from GY or don’t so you can get Bibliomuse and Deus-X from Deck during your opponent’s Standby Phase. I prefer this over Pot either way. So that gives you Silhouhatte Rabbit with a Spell/Trap pop when you Special Summon a card from your Spell/Trap Zone, Silhouhatte Trick which is 1 to 2 targeted negates on its Summon, Hyper Dragon Cannon which Quick Effect discards a card to pop a card your opponent controls, Tarotrei who flips Tarotreith face-up during your opponent’s Standby, Tarotreith’s Flip Effect getting you Deus-X which is a continuous monster effect activation negate after Tarotreith flips it face-up, and Underworld Ritual in GY gets you Bibliomuse from Deck who can be flipped face-up with Tarotreith and her Flip Effect gives you 2 searches for follow-up. All of your Monster Zones are filled including your EMZ, so you will have to either wait for your opponent to clear a monster for you to use Silhouhatte Trick. Normally, I would clear my field with I:P’s effect to Link Summon, but we were locked into LIGHT monsters from the Extra Deck. Furthermore, this is a really nice combo as it has the non-Prediction Princess side of the Deck on our endboard for interruption whereas these Decks that I make experimenting with different Level 9’s usually forgo that monster once I use it to make Aggregator, so it is nice to see this.

For the non-Ritual combo, you just need X-Cross Cannon. Normal Cannon and activate its effect to equip B-Buster Drake from Deck to it. Unequip B-Buster Drake to Special Summon it. Link them off into Platinum Gadget. Buster Drake triggers in GY to search for Y-Dragon Yearhead from Deck. Activate Platinum Gadget to Special Y-Dragon from hand. Y-Dragon activates equipping Buster Drake from GY. Banish Plat Gadget and Y-Dragon to Special Summon Union Controller from Extra Deck into the EMZ. Union Controller Chain Link 1 and Buster Drake Chain Link 2. Buster Drake searches for Z-Zillion Tank and Controller searches for Union Hangar. Activate Hangar which searches for another Z-Zillion Tank. Activate Union Controller to Special Summon Z-Zillion Tank from hand. Chain Link 1 Z-Zillion Tank and Chain Link 2 Union Hangar. Union Hangar equips Union Driver from Deck to Tank and Tank equips Y-Dragon from banished to itself. Unequip Y-Dragon to Special Summon it and activate its effect to equip Z-Zillion from hand to it. The equipped Z-Zillion unequips itself to Special Summon itself. Union Driver banishes itself to equip Torque Tuner Gear from Deck to Tank. Unequip Torque Tune Gear to Special Summon itself. Now, looking at your field, you have Union Controller in the EMZ, 2 Z-Zillion Tank, 1 Y-Dragon Yearhead, and 1 Torque Tune Gear. We can do several things here, so I will go through all of them. (1) you can Synchro Tune Gear and Union Controller into F.A. Dawn Dragster. Then, you can Link a Tank and Y-Dragon into Silhouhatte Rabbit who sets Silhouhatte Trick from Deck. And finally, you can banish X-Cross Cannon, Y-Dragon Yearhead, and Z-Zillion Tank for Hyper Dragon Cannon. This gives you a pop with Hyper Dragon Cannon, a Spell/Trap negate with Dawn Dragster, a Spell/Trap pop with Rabbit when you get out Hatte Trick, and Hatte Trick is 1-2 targeted negates on Summon. (2) You can Link 4 monsters with different names off into Knightmare Gryphon. Then, you could use its effect to get a Normal Spell like Terraforming, Pot of Prosperity, or even Pre-Preparation of Rites from GY and set it for next turn if you did get them into GY previously. Next, banish the materials for Hyper Dragon Cannon and Summon it to Linkpoint. This gives you a potential follow-up if you set a card off of Gryphon, a pop off of Hyper Dragon Cannon, and Gryphon itself prevents monster effect activations of Special Summoned monsters on the field unless they are Linked. It’s not great, but considering we are LIGHT-locked, this is something you could be doing. (3) Link Union Controller and a Level 4 into Silhouhatte Rabbit and set Hatte Trick. Tune Torque Tune Gear and a Level 4 into Denglong, First of the Yang Zing, and if you sided in a copy of Nine Pillars of the Yang Zing, you can use Denglong to search for that. Then, Synchro Denglong and the remaining Level 4 into Chaofeng, Phantom of the Yang Zing before banishing the materials for Hyper Dragon Cannon and Summoning it. This gives you a Spell/Trap pop off of Rabbit when you Summon Hatte Trick, 1-2 targeted negates when Hatte Trick is Special Summoned, a pop off of Hyper Dragon Cannon, your opponent cannot activate LIGHT monster effects while Chaofeng is on the field, and you have an omni-negate in Nine Pillars which does get rid of your Chaofeng but it still does provide good interruption. The fourth option would be to do Fiendsmith combos by going into Moon of the Closed Heaven first to end on a Fiendsmith Dies Irae, but we aren’t playing those cards.
Ritual Beasts BD
CyDra

deck_excerpt: The R4NK Revival is upon us...
deck_description:
TL;DR: The Raizeols that search are all 1 card combo starters. Max out on them and put other Raizeol cards to 1, except Node for the mid to late game. Max out on Bonfire and Seventh Tachyon for added consistency. Running the Toy Engine for Rank 4 fodder and for Ice and Node's effects that require you to send a card to GY. Also Toy Soldier can search for the Box, Ice or Ex and opening 2 Boxes is full combo. Running the Tachyon cards for easy counter trap access because otherwise the deck loses to board breakers. Also Primal can search Seventh tachyon as well as Transmigration. Not running Rafflesia becuase the Field Spell does the same job but better and I'm running F0 for vibes mostly but you do end your turn on 3 Xyz monsters so Hole Thruster's (PAUSE) GY eff can hard summon it during your opp turn.

----------

----------

Not sure how to start this so I'll just get into it. I haven't seen a list on this site similar to mine so I thought I'll share it for others to see.

For those unaware, Raizeol is essentially modern day Rank 4 turbo. Think Spright but instead of Level/Rank/Link 2, it's Level/Rank 4. In my opinion, I think it's the most complete deck coming out of Crossover Breakers and has potential. It's very consistent, has space for about 20 non-engine, can play around/through handtraps and has decent endboards. Now I'll go through the ratios. Starting with the Raizeol cards.

Ice Raizeol , Thode Raizeol  and Ex Raizeol are all run at 3 as they are 1 card combo starters. Ice = Ex < Sword, in terms of starting potential. Ice and Ex produce the same endboard while Sword produces a slightly weaker board. I'm running 2 Node Raizeol  (instead of 1) because it's good to have after the first turn. It gets rid of used up Xyz so you can make another one. (The field spell prevents you from summoning an Xyz monster if you have a copy on the field). Only running 1 Palma Raizeol as a searchable extender. Its effect can be relevant to get over stuff and I think it's interesting that it foolishes ANY level 4, e.g. you could send Shaddoll Dragon to make it a 3100 beater and then pop a Spell/Trap (very funny but bad) but it very rarely comes up. Raizeol Cross , Raizeol Plug-In and Raizeol Hole Thruster (No Diddy) are all run at 1. They're all good cards but they dont help further plays (besides Plug-in) and are all searchable. You'd rather see non-engine in your hand.

Bonfire and Seventh Tachyon are must plays. With Seventh Tachyon, I'm also running Number 104: Masquerade and Number 105: Battlin' Boxer Star Cestus as targets. Bonfire searches Ice and Ex, while Seventh Tachyon searches all your non-Handtrap monsters. With these two cards we have 15 starters which is why I mentioned before that the deck is very consistent.

Now onto the techs. I'm running two engines. A Toy Box engine and a very small Tachyon engine. For the Toy Box engine, I'm running 3 Toy Box , 1 Toy Soldier and 1 Toy Tank . Ice Raizeol and Node Raizeol have effects that require you to send a card from your hand or field to the GY and so you can use the Toys you set with Toy Box as fodder for these effects which will activate the Toys' effects to summon themselves, giving you more material for Rank 4s. The Toys can be Set as Spells from the Hand, so opening them is not a problem. Also Toy Soldier can search for Toy Box on Summon to set Toys or search for any Level 4 LIGHT if you already control Toy Box, which includes Ice Raizeol and Ex Raizeol. One more thing to note is that Toy Box is not a HOPT and that opening 2 is full combo. You can Set the Toys with the first and then pop both Toys with the second which will summon both and allow you to search Ice or Ex with Toy Soldier starting your plays.

For the Tachyon engine, I'm running 1 Galaxy-Eyes Tachyon Primal and 1 Tachyon Transmigration in the Main and 1 Galaxy Photon Dragon in the Extra. Any 2 Level 4s can make Galaxy Photon Dragon which searches Primal and Primal searches Transmigration. Primal is a Galaxy-Eyes monster which makes Transmigration live. Raizeols has no in engine Spell/Trap negate which means that it can fare pretty badly against board breakers like Evenly Matched or Forbidden Droplet . Getting to the counter trap prevents that (as long as they only open 1). Opening Primal isn't the best but it still searches the counter trap if you can make Galaxy Photon Dragon. Also Primal searches for any Tachyon Spell/Trap which includes our searcher spell Seventh Tachyon, so if you open Transmigration, Primal can search for that instead giving you extension or follow up for next turn as it can search the Raizeols and the Toys.

The other 12 cards can be whatever you want. I'm currently using those slots for handtraps.

As for the Extra Deck, I think it's pretty self explanatory for the most part. I'm running 2 of both Raizeol Xyz, Raizeol Deadnader and Raizeol Duodrive , they're both great cards and we want to have plays for when our board gets broken. Mereologic Aggregator is special here. It's never summoned and only used for it GY effect. Ex Raizeol can send it to the GY to summon itself and Deadnader can attach it from the GY to then detach to activate its efffect again. This makes Ex Raizeol really good going second as it forces your opponents hand and Aggregator's effect can chain block Ex's search.

Two more things to mention. One is the lack of Traptrix Rafflesia . I think Rafflesia is a good card but after the field spell was revealed I don't think it's needed anymore. Cross does what Rafflesia does but better and it's searchable by Duodrive. Also not going into Rafflesia allows you to go into Galaxy Photon Dragon and get Transmigration.

The other thing to mention is Number F0: Utopic Draco Future . It's not a Rank 4 so you can't go into it through the normal routes. My normal endboard is Cross + Duodrive (with Hole Thruster attached), Galaxy Photon Dragon + Primal + Transmigration and Deadnader with 3 pops including an Aggregator, sometimes you'll also have an Abyss Dweller. After negating an effect with Cross and detaching the Hole Thruster, you can then banish the Hole Thruster (after you've used up your interruptions) to hard make F0 using the Duodrive, Galaxy Photon Dragon and Deadnader/Dweller for another interruption. You could also run Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder and wait for your opponent to attack one of your Xyz and then make it in their Battle Phase which is funny. Deadnader can protect your Xyz by battle so it's easier than you might think to access.

That's all I've got to say. Thanks for reading.
Just a little budget Plunder Patroll deck

7 months ago when I made my Superheavy Samurai and Karakuri Prediction Princess Deck, I said that Blue-Eyes Prediction Princess is a Deck that could not work as Blue-Eyes Spirit Dragon prevented you from Special Summoning 2 or more monsters at the same time, preventing you from activating World Legacy Monstrosity targeting it for 2 Level 9 monsters from the Deck and due to Azure-Eyes Silver Dragon having a mandatory effect on Special Summon that prevented both players from targeting Dragon monsters you currently controlled with card effects which also stopped you from targeting it with Monstrosity. However, the Advent of Blue-Eyes Structure Deck that is coming out in the future changed that. It gives us 1 card that basically simplifies the combo to get to Blue-Eyes Spirit Dragon while also allowing you to get both Spirit Dragon and Azure-Eyes out onto the field as 2 Level 9 monsters to go into Mereologic Aggregator. In short, the Link-1 Spirit with Eyes of Blue turns Sage with Eyes of Blue into a 1-card combo that gets us straight to Mereologic Aggregator without having to jump through complicated loops to get there. And surprisingly, this has become one of the most impressive Prediction Princess Decks that I have worked with so far. Sage being a 1-card combo for Aggregator means that you just need to draw either Prediction Princess Bibliomuse or either Ritual Monster or a copy of the Ritual Spell for full Prediction Princess combo. So that means that we also get to play a lot of non-engine cards as well which is a new feeling, especially for Prediction Princess. We are killing 2 birds with 1 stone today since Blue-Eyes has 2 Level 9 monsters. Blue-Eyes Spirit Dragon is a Level 9 LIGHT Dragon Synchro Monster that requires a Tuner and 1 or more non-Tuner Blue-Eyes monsters. While it is on the field, neither player can Special Summon 2 or more monsters at the same time. As a soft opt during either player’s turn, you can negate the activation of a card in the GY and as a non-opt during either player’s turn while it was previously Synchro Summoned, you can Tribute it to Special Summon a LIGHT Dragon Synchro Monster from your Extra Deck except for itself but it is destroyed during the End Phase. Azure-Eyes Silver Dragon is a Level 9 LIGHT Dragon Synchro Monster that requires a Tuner and 1 or more non-Tuner Normal Monsters as material. It has a mandatory effect that activates on Special Summon that prevents either player from targeting Dragon monsters you currently control with card effects or destroying them with card effects until the end of the next turn. And as a once per turn during your Standby Phase, you can target and Special Summon a Normal Monster from your GY. So, the way we are getting 2 Level 9’s on field is by Synchro Summoning Spirit Dragon, Tributing it off to Summon Azure-Eyes from Extra Deck, and then Tributing Spirit with Eyes of Blue to use its effect to bring back Spirit Dragon. Sage with Eyes of Blue is full combo to get to Aggregator, so we just need any Prediction Princess card for full Prediction Princess combo. Let’s say that we draw Sage and Tarotrei. Normal Sage and use its effect on Normal Summon to search for Maiden with Eyes of Blue. Link Sage into the Link-1 Spirit and use its effect on Link Summon to add Mausoleum of White from Deck to hand. Activate Mausoleum and use its additional Normal Summon to Normal Summon Maiden. Activate Mausoleum’s other effect targeting Maiden. Maiden triggers on Chain Link 2 to Special Summon Blue-Eyes White Dragon from hand, Deck, or GY. Mausoleum resolves sending another copy of Blue-Eyes from hand or Deck to GY. Synchro Maiden and Blue-Eyes into Spirit Dragon. Tribute Spirit Dragon to Summon Azure-Eyes from Extra Deck. Then activate the Link-1 to Tribute it to bring back Spirit Dragon. Xyz Azure-Eyes and Spirit Dragon into Mereologic Aggregator in the EMZ who sends Herald of the Arc Light from Extra Deck to GY which triggers to search for Underworld Ritual of Prediction. Detach a material from Aggregator to target and reattach Herald from GY. Link Aggregator into Gravity Controller which triggers Herald in GY to search for Prediction Princess Tarotreith. Activate Underworld Ritual tributing Tarotreith to Ritual Summon Tarotrei. During the End Phase, Tarotrei Special Summons Tarotreith from GY face-down. And then during your opponent’s Standby Phase, you can banish Underworld Ritual from GY to get Bibliomuse from Deck face-down and you can flip Tarotreith face-up with Tarotrei’s effect to get either Deus-X Krawler or Pot of the Forbidden from Deck with both Bibliomuse and whatever Flip Monster you Summoned being able to be flipped up by Tarotreith to get their effects.

For the Main Deck Monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 2 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during your End Phase. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's effect in the End Phase. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-downn and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back face-down after being Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s card effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent's side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute. 1 Pot of the Forbidden which has a Flip Effect that lets you choose between Drawing 2 cards, returning all Spell/Traps on the field to the hand, destroying all monsters your opponent controls, or looking at your opponent's hand and shuffling a card from it back into the Deck. 2 Blue-Eyes White Dragon. 1 Maiden with Eyes of Blue. I think that she is much better in application for this Deck than the new Maiden of White is. We are using her for her first effect only which is when a card or effect activates that targets her, you can Quick Effect Special Summon a Blue-Eyes White Dragon from your hand, Deck, or GY. Maiden of White can only Summon Blue-Eyes from your GY, but she is designed to have more focus on getting out Blue-Eyes Spirit Ultimate Dragon anyways. 3 Sage with Eyes of Blue which adds a Level 1 LIGHT Tuner monster from your Deck to your hand except for itself on Normal Summon. And you can discard it and target an Effect Monster you control to send it to the GY to Special Summon a Blue-Eyes monster from Deck. In a normal Blue-Eyes Deck, Sage’s second effect is really good for accessing a Blue-Eyes from Deck, and we could also use that in this Deck as well since we could use it to get Blue-Eyes Abyss Dragon which searches for a Ritual Spell on Special Summon. However, that would just be making things more complicated than they need to be, so just using Sage for his first effect is good enough. 3 Ash Blossom and 2 Effect Veiler. Veiler is also a Level 1 LIGHT Tuner Monster FYI, so you could search it off of the new Prayers with Eyes of Blue if you already have Sage for an interruption.

Spell/Traps: 1 Instant Fusion for Master of Ham. 3 Pot of Prosperity. 1 Foolish Burial. Remember that Underworld Ritual can also Ritual Summon from GY, so this is basically another copy of either of the Ritual Monsters. 3 Prayer with Eyes of Blue. This card discards a card to search for a Level 1 LIGHT Tuner Monster and a Spell/Trap that mentions Blue-Eyes White Dragon except for another copy of itself. And you can banish it from GY to target a Blue-Eyes White Dragon you control to equip it with a Blue-Eyes monster from your Extra Deck as an Equip Spell that gives it 400 ATK. Aside from searching for Sage or Effect Veiler, this card also gets you to the new Blue-Eyes Trap which I will talk about when I get to it. Its GY effect helps you Summon Blue-Eyes Tyrant Dragon in a normal Blue-Eyes Deck, but it can also set you up for Dragon Master Magia by putting Blue-Eyes Ultimate Dragon into rotation. We can actually make Dragon Master Magia and ensure it has a Monster and a Spell negate. We would just need to play Ultimate Fusion as well as a way to a BLS monster or a Chaos monster like playing Black Luster Soldier - Legendary Swordsman, Blue-Eyes Chaos Dragon, Blue-Eyes Chaos MAX Dragon, or by playing Summoner of Illusions for Master of Chaos. Or even by playing Witch Doctor of Chaos if you’re freaky like that. But that means that we would be putting a bunch of otherwise useless cards in our Deck which is not great, so continuing on with what we have is great. 1 Mausoleum of White which gives you an additional Normal Summon of a Level 1 LIGHT Tuner Monster in addition to your Normal Summon/Set and the only other effect we are using it for is having it target a face-up monster we control to send a Normal Monster from hand or Deck to GY to increase the targeted monster’s ATK/DEF by that monster’s Level x100. We just need this targeting effect to trigger Maiden’s effect. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down. 1 Called By the Grave and 2 Crossout Designator. 3 Infinite Impermanence. And finally, 1 Majesty with Dragons of White which allows you to show up to 3 Blue-Eyes White Dragon(s) from your hand, face-up Monster Zone, and/or GY to destroy that many cards your opponent controls. We aren’t using its GY effect as much as feel like how cool it would be to do so in thai Deck. This card is our Spell/Trap target that mentions Blue-Eyes White Dragon to search off of Prayers. And to be honest, 2 pops is actually pretty good all things considered. You could also play a second copy if you are worried you draw it and turn off your Prayer.

Extra Deck: 1 Master of Ham which can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or Deck face-down on Fusion Summon. 1 Blue-Eyes Spirit Dragon and 1 Azure-Eyes Silver Dragon. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which adds a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from your Deck to your hand if it is sent to the GY. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder. 1 Super Starslayer TY-PHON - Sky Crisis. 1 Infinitrack Earth Slicer. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 S:P Little Knight and 1 Gravity Controller. And 1 Spirit with Eyes of Blue which is the new Link-1 for Blue-Eyes. It needs either a Level 4 or lower Dragon or Spellcaster for Material and it locks you into Special Summoning Dragons while it is on the field (which is not an issue for how we are using it). On Link Summon, it can add or send a Mausoleum of White from Deck. And you can Tribute it to Special Summon a Blue-Eyes monster from hand or GY, but if you Summon an Effect Monster from GY by this effect, its effects are negated and it cannot attack. This is literally the card that I needed to make Blue-Eyes Prediction Princess work. It literally does everything I need to get 2 Level 9’s onto the field which is just unbelievable. 

Side Deck: 3 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Kashtira Fenrir, 3 Dark Ruler No More, 2 Lightning Storm, 1 Harpie’s Feather Duster, and 3 Evenly Matched.
Stupid Unchained

deck_excerpt: Control deck that is able to summon big ATK monsters to finish off your opponents quickly after you stabilized.
deck_description:
PROS

- Good Control options.

- One sided acrhetype floodgate in Awakening of the Sacred Beasts .

CONS

-Bricky

-Handtraps can slow you down seriously.

 

General About the Deck

The main idea is to use Sacred Beasts here , for that reason ive picked Crystal Beasts to pair with them for their ability to get relatively easy 3 monsters or 3 continuous spells on the field to properly summon the Sacred Beasts Hamon, Lord of Striking Thunder and Raviel, Lord of Phantasms which also makes them able to be resummoned every turn via Hyper Blaze . Using a variety of control options provided by Crystal Beasts we can stabilize to end the game with the strong Sacred Beasts or Extra Deck options.

Main Deck

3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring and 3 Infinite Impermanence as our handtraps , because the deck is quite bricky ive opted to keep the handtrap count at 6 total with 3 more in sideboard if needed.

Hamon, Lord of Striking Thunder and Raviel, Lord of Phantasms are our sacred beasts , Uria, Lord of Searing Flames is hanging at the sideboard because he is the worst of the 3 and very situational. We use one of each since they are bricks usually and we dont want to see them before wanting to use them.

A single copy of Awakening of the Sacred Beasts since its searchable by Dark Beckoning Beast , this card is a strong onesided floodgate that needs you to put some work to make use of. Also lets you recover continious traps from the graveyard if you have a lv10 monster on the field(usually a Sacred Beast) which synergizes with Crystal Conclave.

Cerulean Skyfire has the ability to negate spell/traps with the added bonus that the way its written it can negate cards that you usually cant interact with , like Super Polymerization , but you need an attack position Hamon, Lord of Striking Thunder to access this effect, the other notable effect is it makes you take no damage for the rest of the turn if a Sacred Beast has left your field which helps you survive. And finaly it has a good bonus effect that lets you use facedown spells of any type in addition to continuous spells to summon Hamon, Lord of Striking Thunder . One copy since its useless without Hamon, Lord of Striking Thunder and its searchable by Dark Beckoning Beast .

Hyper Blaze is a searcher for the Sacred Beasts that also allows you to resummon them if you have summoned the properly before.

3 Dark Beckoning Beast is our main Sacred Beast searcher since its able to search for every spell/trap/monster of the archetype , but only on normal summon.

3 Opening of the Spirit Gates to search for our Sacred Beast related monsters and use as extender to bring out Raviel, Lord of Phantasms or some Extra Deck Link monster.

Chaos Summoning Beast and Dark Summoning Beast are used as 1 copy each since you dont want to see them usually , you want to search them when you need them via Opening of the Spirit Gates or Dark Beckoning Beast . They let you summon your Sacred Beasts ignoring their summoning conditions for when you need them on the field fast.

3 Rainbow Bridge is a non once per turn searcher for Crystal spell/traps.

3 Crystal Bond is technicaly a 1 for 2 searcher for Crystal Beasts since it gets you one on the hand and one on the spell/trap zone.

3 Rainbow Bridge of the Heart is everything you need , its a searcher an extender and disruption.

Awakening of the Crystal Ultimates is a bit bricky if you dont have an Ultimate Crystal on hand thats why we use it as one copy to search when we can use it, the Ultimate Crystal we use in this deck is Rainbow Dark Dragon since its the most realistic Ultimate Crystal to summon by banishing 7 Dark Monsters with different names from the graveyard, unrealistic but possible with help from Extra Deck, unlike regular Crystal Beast Rainbow Dragon .

3 Crystal Beast Sapphire Pegasus can search for your Crystal Beast monsters, mostly used to search for Crystal Beast Rainbow Dragon so that it can in turn search for your Rainbow Dark Dragon to get out of the deck and extend with another Crystal Beast.

3 Crystal Beast Rainbow Dragon even though 2 are usually enough , you need Crystal Beasts to use your Crystal spell/traps , especialy Rainbow Bridge of the Heart , on top of beeing able to easier summon 2 of them to go into Garunix Eternity, Hyang of the Fire Kings if needed.

Crystal Beast Cobalt Eagle  as a 4th lv4 Wind Type Crystal beast to use for Lightning Chidori or some other Rank4 XYZ.

Crystal Beast Ruby Carbuncle is an excellent extender that helps you special summon all of your backrow Crystal Beasts.

Crystal Promise another good extender card usually paired with Crystal Beast Ruby Carbuncle .

Awakening of the Crystal Ultimates is a versaliate card that needs you to play a brick in your deck and is also a brick if you dont have an Ultimate Crystal in hand or field , but the versatility it offers is worth it.

Crystal Master for the measly cost of your normal summon can search for almost every card on the Crystal Beast side of the deck.

Crystal Conclave is your main interaction on the opposing turn , bounce effect is simple and efficient , bypasses destruction and "sent to graveyard" effects of opposing cards.

Crystal Miracle is the another form of interaction , strong and searchable omni negate and destroy effect.
