deck_excerpt: Call it a Red-Eyes Deck if you can
deck_description:
Just like with Blue-Eyes, I did say that Red-Eyes could not make a Prediction Princess Deck work, specifically referring to Red-Eyes Darkness Dragon, Archfiend Black Skull Dragon, and Black Skull Dragon. However, I digress as I just kept slamming my head against the wall to make Archfiend Black Skull and Black Skull Dragon to work. And to a degree, it does work, but this is on a level even below that of Metalfoes Prediction Princess. I would like to thank Primoredial Tremors first and foremost for being Unexpected Dai for any Normal Monster since it beats having to draw an unsearchable vanilla monster and it actually provides interruption if you can believe that. I am kicking Red-Eyes Darkness Dragon to the curb today to focus on Archfiend Black Skull Dragon and Black Skull Dragon. Black Skull Dragon is a Level 9 DARK Dragon non-Effect Fusion Monster that requires Summoned Skull and Red-Eyes Black Dragon as Fusion Material. Archfiend Black Skull is a Level 9 DARK Dragon Fusion Monster that requires a Level 6 Archfiend Normal Monster and a Level 7 Red-Eyes Normal Monster as Fusion Material. It can only be Special Summoned once per turn. Your opponent cannot activate cards or effects until the end of the damage step when it battles and at the end of the Battle Phase in which this card was involved in damage calculation with this Fusion Summoned card, you can target a Red-Eyes Normal Monster in your GY, inflict damage to your opponent equal to its ATK in the GY and shuffle it back into the Deck. You can literally see multiple points of back-pedaling just by reading this card. Red-Eyes became such a powerful burn strategy, albeit a really bad and in-coherently inconsistent one, thanks to Konami when they were making the first Legendary Duelists. Just look at this card: it can only Special Summoned once per turn and it has to be Fusion Summoned and have been involved in damage calculation to burn your opponent. But probably the most baffling part of this card is its Fusion Materials. Just say that you need Red-Eyes and Summoned Skull to Fusion Summon this card. I understand that there exist Red-Eyes Gemini Monsters, but the materials for this card are quite literally the same as the original Black Skull Dragon even though it’s supposed to be a retrain. Anyways, this Deck focuses on Fusion Summoning Black Skull Dragon while also searching for World Legacy Monstrosity through the Predaplant Red Resonator engine, but you will need access to either Red-Eyes or Summoned Skull to get there. And if we have access to both of them, we can Summon both Black Skull Dragon and Archfiend Black Skull Dragon for literally no reason other than psychological damage to our opponent, making them question why we are playing such terrible cards and then performing Ritual Prediction Princess combos with them instead of playing Red-Eyes. Combo is Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio, Red Resonator, a monster to send for Scorpio, and access to either Red-Eyes Black Dragon or Summoned Skull. Let’s just say that we drew Summoned Skull for this scenario. Normal Red Resonator and use it to Special Scorpio from hand, Scorpio sends a monster from hand (other than the Summoned Skull) to Special Summon Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra from Deck, and Cobra triggers to search for Ultra Polymerization. Activate Ultra Poly to fuse Cobra and Scorpio into Predaplant Ambulomelides. Ambulo triggers on Fusion Summon to search for Predaplant Bufolicula. Banish Ultra Poly from GY targeting Ambulo to Special Summon back Cobra and Scorpio from GY. Synchro Red Resonator and Cobra into Ib the World Chalice Justiciar who searches World Legacy Monstrosity on Summon. Ambulo tributes Scorpio to Special Summon another Bufolicula from Deck. Synchro Bufo and Ib into Muddy Mudragon. Ib floats into World Chalice Guardragon. Scale Bufo and use its Pend Effect to Fuse Muddy Mudragon and Summoned Skull into Black Skull Dragon. Target it with Monstrosity to get Bibliomuse and Deus-X from Deck. And just make Aggregator sending Herald and the rest is basic Prediction Princess combo. If we drew both Red-Eyes and Summoned Skull, we could’ve Fused both of them from hand first with Bufo into Black Skull Dragon and then bring back one of them with Guardragon to Fuse via the effect of Muddy Mudragon into Archfiend Black Skull. Or if we got the Red-Eyes off of Primoredial Tremors beforehand, we could’ve fused using Muddy Mudragon and Red-Eyes on field first for Black Skull before bring it back with Guardragon to Fuse it with Summoned Skull in hand for Archfiend Black Skull. With Red-Eyes being such a disjointed archetype with it having basically a mishmash of different identities, it is much harder to work with than its counterpart of Blue-Eyes which gets way more support and actually has a coherent Deck and archetypal identity.

For the Main Deck Monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during your End Phase. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's effect in the End Phase. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-downn and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back face-down after being Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s card effects. 2 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent's side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute. 1 Red-Eyes Black Dragon and 1 Summoned Skull. 3 Predaplant Ophrys Scorpio which sends a monster from your hand to GY on Normal or Special Summon to Special Summon a Predaplant monster from Deck and 1 Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra which searches for a Fusion or Polymerization Spell from Deck if Special Summoned by the effect of a Predaplant monster. 2 Predaplant Bufolicula which we are just using for its Pendulum Effect which Fusion Summons a DARK Fusion Monster from your Extra Deck using monsters from your hand or field as Fusion Material. 2 Lonefire Blossom which can Tribute a Plant to Summon a Plant from Deck. 1 World Chalice Guardragon to Special Summon off of Ib and it can banish itself from GY to Special Summon back a Normal Monster from GY to Linkpoint. 3 Red Resonator which can Special Summon a Level 4 or lower monster from your hand on Normal Summon or target 1 monster on the field on Special Summon to gain LP equal to that monster’s ATK.

Spell/Traps: 1 Instant Fusion for Master of Ham. 3 Pot of Prosperity. 3 Primoredial Tremors. This card pays 2000 LP and has you declare the name of a Normal Monster. If you control no monsters, you can Special Summon the Normal Monster whose name you declared from your Deck and Normal Monsters with the declared name and Primoredial monsters cannot be destroyed by battle until the end of your opponent’s turn. Also, if your opponent Normal Summons a monster, you can banish this card from your GY and target a Normal Monster you control or n your GY to banish 1 monster on the field with lower ATK. 2 Summoner’s Art which searches for a Level 5 or higher Normal Monster. 3 Resonator Call which searches for a Resonator monster. 1 World Legacy Monstrosity which either Special Summons a Level 9 monster from hand or targets a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different Type and Attribute than that monster but with different names. 1 Ultra Polymerization which pays 2000 LP to Fusion Summon using 2 monsters you control where neither player can activate cards or effects in response to the activation and you can banish it from GY to target a Fusion Monster that was Summoned by its effect to Special Summon the monsters used for its Summon from GY with their effects negated and ATK/DEF changed to 0. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which Ritual Summons a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down. And you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down.

Extra Deck: 1 Archfiend Black Skull Dragon and 1 Black Skull Dragon. 1 Predaplant Ambulomelides which adds a Predap card on Fusion Summon and can target and Tribute a monster to Special Summon a Predaplant monster from your Deck. 1 Master of Ham which Special Summons a Flip Monster from hand or Deck on Fusion Summon. 1 Muddy Mudragon which can Substitute itself for a named Fusion Material and it can Fusion Summon a Fusion Monster from your Extra Deck by using monsters you control as Material including itself. 1 Ib the World Chalice Justiciar which adds a World Legacy card from Deck to hand on Synchro Summon and floats into a World Chalice monster when sent from field to GY. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which searches for a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell if sent to the GY. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 S:P Little Knight, 1 I:P Masquerena, and 1 Lib the World Key Blademaster. 

Side Deck: 3 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Kashtira Fenrir, 3 Dark Ruler No More, 1 Harpie’s Feather Duster, 2 Lightning Storm, and 3 Evenly Matched.

My custom centurion decklist. Made for how I like to play and for fun.

Starry Knight was a pretty underwhelming theme for its time, and that hasn't changed, but having synergies with the much better Voiceless Voice decktype allows this deck to be a much more interesting control deck than before. The new Sauravis is basically begging to be played in Starry Knight. It returns itself to the hand which triggers Orbitael in GY among other effects, and sets itself up to be resummoned by something like SK Ceremony. Ancient & Ascended (AKA old Sauravis) is phenomenal for interrupting Synchro, Xyz and Link Summons and dodging effects like imperm or targeted removal once in your hand, making it useful for both setup and grind games.

 

Make use of both archetypes' Continuous Spells to plus every turn. A fun trick is having Ceremony + a set Blast and returning a L7LDragon to hand to activate the Blast. Ceremony then immediately summons it back.

 

This deck is very WIP but I'd love to see some other experimentation with it. Ties of the Brethren is used in some other Starry Knight builds but imo it's too risky drawing it for turn in a clutch situation. That said my words are by no means gospel and I think you shouldn't be afraid to experiment if you build this deck too.

deck_excerpt: The aspiring "Master of Faster" has new tools to try out in the Red Dragon Archfiend strategy!
deck_description:
The aspiring "Master of Faster" has new tools in their arsenal to try out in the Red Dragon Archfiend Strategy - Shining Star Dragon and Red Lotus King!

 

First of all, Shining Star Dragon grants the deck access to a monster boardwipe during your opponent's Main Phase! Using Shining Star Dragon to "quick-synch" into the generically accessible Centur-Ion Auxilia (which happens to be a dark dragon monster) fulfills Scarred Dragon Archfiend's conditional fieldwipe! 

 

Red Lotus King, Flame Crime acts as an additional extender for the strategy, allowing Red Dragon to play past the handtraps that are all too common in this format. It also sends any normal trap from deck to GY, allowing Red Dragon to finally easily access its power array of trap cards like Red Reign (field wipe) and Time to Stand Up! (monster negate).

The deck also works and melds incredibly well with Bystials very much like Dragonlink or Branded, netting you additional resources, interruption, extenders, beatsticks and combo pieces. 
 
BE THE CRIMSON KING WITH RED DRAGON ARCHFIEND! ABSOLUTE POWERFORCE!!! SYNNKRROOOO SHOOOKKAAAAANNNNN!!!

If you want a more detailed guide on how to pilot this deck, please check out my earlier article on Red Dragon Archfiend from a couple months ago. 
 
GLHF Duelists!
 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

A "Batalha da Cidade" é um arco importante em Yu-Gi-Oh!. A história tem origem no antigo Egito, onde magos enfrentam o lendário Zork, uma ameaça constante ao país. Para se defenderem, eles utilizam a magia de um livro proibido, criando as Relíquias do Milênio, poderosos artefatos mágicos. O faraó Aknamkanon, em meio a conflitos com outras nações, decide usar essas relíquias, sem saber o preço que pagaria.

 

Essas Relíquias do Milênio desempenham um papel crucial na trama, cada uma com habilidades únicas, como o Enigma do Milênio, que contém o espírito do Faraó, e o Olho do Milênio, que concede visões especiais.

 

Durante a Batalha da Cidade, ocorrem duelos intensos entre duelistas, incluindo Yugi, Seto Kaiba, e Joey Wheeler. Além disso, cartas icônicas como o "Pote da Ganância", que permite ao jogador sacar duas cartas do baralho, são introduzidas nessa saga.

deck_excerpt: Why this deck will be very good
deck_description:
Played like 50 games and this deck is crazy. Sometimes just feels unstoppable, because every card is broken.

Rank 4 pool feels weird. I feel like it has answers to every problem, but they all feel a little underwhelming because Deadnader and its support are so broken. 

Going first feels insane because its so hard to pin down with one interaction. You must stop the Duodrive, but even then if you get to Deadnader with an Aggregator and 1-2 handtraps, which is lightwork, you're still favored in so many match-ups including Tenpai, which is broken.

Going second feels fine at best, which is insane, but the deck can play as much good stuff as it wants. There are no bad cards. Palma is bad and that doesn't matter, every other card is so good that you literally don't have to play bad cards in the main deck, so every hand is broken. You can play as many handtraps as you want to slow your opoonent, and balance it with as many boardbreakers and other non-engine you want to supplement it with, even weird meta calls.

This is the list I made with that in mind. Which is broken.

 

I figured the deck is so simple that I wanted to supplement it with every simple card I could think of. Got a little weird with Ghost Mourner, that was my preference for that slot, but I was really happy with it. Book of Moon was really good, idea was I can set something immune to destruction and then Deadnader pops it, but it turns out the card is still just good against everything. The "Tactics" cards are insane in this deck. The deck is broken because when you use Talents you will almost never be drawing 2. Palma is the only card is the deck that doesn't feel good so im gonna try 2 thrust because every single card in the deck is good, but the Ryzeal cards in particular are broken.

3 Deadnader because it's just so good. 2 Duodrive because it searches 2 good cards everytime. 1 Mereologic Aggregator because it is the 3rd best card in the extra deck when combined with EX Ryzeal. Everything else is optional. Basically I put in a card for every situation I could think of. Dark Rebellion covers things with big attacks, Light Dragon handles plain monsters, Honor Ark handles monsters safely, Tornado Dragon handles S/Ts, Exciton is a comeback tool, Bagooska and Zeus feel like filler, and Laplacian is win-more, but sometimes is exactly what you need to blow a game out. Before you build for tournament you will have to put a Gagaga Cowboy in the main 15 or the side because the time rules are broken.

Haven't had this much fun with a deck in a long time. Has an incredibly simple gameplan that is hard to stop and hard to break, while giving you enough tools to get creative and solve complicated situations. Deck does have a key weakness in Deadnader being turned off or removed before it can't start hitting, but even then you will still have access to powerful back-ups that can cover a wide-variety of scenarios, but can never cover absolutely everything, meaning that it will some match-up specific decisions it will have to make. Bottom line, its broken.

O Starter Box é o primeiro Deck Inicial no Yu-Gi-Oh! Official Card Game (OCG). Ele foi lançado apenas em japonês. Inicialmente, o lançamento ocorreu nos cinemas em 6 de março de 1999, coincidindo com a estreia japonesa do filme Yu-Gi-Oh! (1999). A data oficial de lançamento mais ampla foi doze dias depois, em 18 de março. Além das cartas, ambas as versões do Starter Box incluíam uma caixa de deck com presilha para cinto, uma calculadora de Pontos de Vida, seis Star Chips e um tapete de jogo.

A Konami substituiu algumas cartas no Starter Box entre os lançamentos nos cinemas e o lançamento oficial. Quem comprou o Starter Box nas exibições de Yu-Gi-Oh! The Movie recebeu "Aqua Madoor", "Trial of Nightmare", "The 13th Grave", "Dark King of the Abyss" e "Turtle Tiger", enquanto na versão oficial de lançamento essas cartas foram substituídas por "Genin", "Kageningen", "Rock Ogre Grotto #2", "King Fog" e "Spiked Snail".Esse conjunto introduziu Monstros de Fusão e Cartas de Campo no OCG. Assim como outras cartas impressas no início do jogo, as cartas no Starter Box não têm números de série impressos e não possuem o holograma do Olho de Anúbis no canto inferior direito de cada carta.

Das cinquenta cartas incluídas no lançamento, todas, exceto onze ("Ancient Tree of Enlightenment", "Genin", "Lunar Queen Elzaim", "Madjinn Gunn", "Masked Clown", "Monsturtle", "Mountain Warrior", "Mystery Hand", "Serpent Marauder", "Spiked Snail" e "Rock Ogre Grotto #2"), foram posteriormente lançadas no Yu-Gi-Oh! Trading Card Game; nenhuma dessas catorze cartas foi relançada no OCG japonês após a Série 1.

Os clientes que fizeram pré-encomenda do Starter Box também receberam uma carta promocional Super Rare chamada "Celtic Guardian".

deck_excerpt: oooh konami you wanna unban spright elf sooooo badddddd 🙏🙏🙏
deck_description:
so im a huge fan of live-twins bc they are super kyute, chronically online little pixels on my screen, and really fun and simple to play (mainly bc they abuse generic links quite a lot). they are by no means meta ofc, BUT it is extremely consistent and has like half the deck open to any hand traps you want so lots of non-engine freedom even tho it runs two engines in the form of twin and spright. deck thrives on flooding your field with a trillion monsters and link climbing, so be very weary of nibiru if you dont open crossout. 

anyways, combos. SO, there are two main lines of combos that you can do--one for each engine, AND ideally, you'll be doing both in the opening turn.

LIVE-TWIN OPENING

twins have 4 starters in the form of secret password, sunny's snitch, pink, and blue. chances are your opening hand will have at least one of these. the spells search other starters and pink and blue special summon each other from deck on summon.

1.) play secret password to search for sunny's snitch even if you already have it in your hand. gives more draw power taking another copy and also baits ash blossom.

2.) play sunny's snitch and activate its trigger effect to search a live-twin. if you have ki-sikil in your hand already, search treat. if you have lil-la in your hand already, search frost. if you have neither in your hand, search lil-la if you don't already have frost in your hand. otherwise, search whatever starter.

3.) next, you'll want to normal summon whatever live-twin starter you have--either pink or blue. on summon, each can special summon the other from hand or deck (or their costumed versions, frost and treat).

4.) assuming you didn't get imperm'd, you should have two twins on field. ideally, you have either frost or treat in your hand, to which you can special summon them from hand as well. you then end with three monsters on field here.

there is more after this with extra deck but since this is a live-twin AND spright deck, before moving on, you wanna do your spright line.

SPRIGHT OPENING

sprights are practically mitosis simulators the way they can essentially special summon themselves for free and fill your board. and well that's exactly what we wanna do if we wanna get into the link climbing silliness. chances are you open with at least one spright card that can get you a body or two or three on field, and those would be spright blue, spright jet, and spright starter. be very careful if using spright starter tho as spright starter will lock you into only being able to summon level/rank/link-2s for the rest of the turn.

1.) this is assuming you already have your twins on the field, but if you don't, just do what you can to get bodies on field. since twins are level 2, any spright monster in your hand can be special summoned to the field for free. carrot and red work, but the ideal scenario is to special summon spright blue and activate its trigger effect to add jet--or carrot if you already have jet--to hand. 

2.) special summon jet to search spright starter or gamma burst. up to your discretion. if going second, gamma burst can set up an OTK with its ATK buffs. starter doesn't need to be played this turn or at least right now unless you really need another body to link climb.

3.) you CAN use starter LATER at the end of the turn or during your opponent's turn to get carrot on the field. carrot will be your friendly, neighborhood omni-negate that loves staying on field if possible.

EXTRA DECK & LINK CLIMBING 

so i don't wanna make this too convoluted here, so i'm just showing visuals of what you want to end on before i explain how to get there with all the other million cards in case you already know what you're doing.

so this will be the best end board going first imo. depends on matchup, i suppose, but this is my go-to. this end board is assuming you are starting with FIVE BODIES on the field. WITH FOUR BODIES, AVOID LINKING INTO MUCKRAKER. just do your evil twins without her, then.

1.) first, you'll want to link two sprights into masquerena. also, just so you don't accidentally misplay, take note of where your links' arrows are pointing to and that you have an open space to summon another. idk how to give a visual with text here, but i believe in you with all my heart.

2.) then, link pink twin and something else (usually blue twin) into evil pink twin. use evil pink's effect to summon back blue twin. THIS WILL LOCK YOU INTO FIENDS FOR THE REST OF THE TURN. but do not fret. this is why we summoned masquerena first. 

3.) link evil pink and blue twin into evil blue. then, use evil blue and your last remaining body to make muckraker. activate muckraker to discard a card and summon back evil blue.

4.) using evil blue and masquerena, link summon unchained abomination. now, your end board should be abom up top with muckraker and evil pink under. on your opponent's turn, when they have at least two cards on field, activating evil pink to bring back evil blue will pop a card. then, abom will trigger and can pop another card. at the end phase, abom can also pop a third card. super annoying for your opponent bc you can stop a lot of combos and extra deck summons on their part with this. also, muckraker can tribute evil pink to negate anything that would destroy one of your monsters. evil blue can then respawn evil pink to get your body back and draw a card with evil pink.

TURN 2

unforunately, it is very difficult to have apollousa turn 1 due to how easy it is to get locked into either Link-2s and/or fiends on the opening combo. however, she is very accessible turn 2. keeping in mind the evil twins can respawn one another, we can get apollousa and trouble sunny, as well, on the field at the same time. 

1.) link evil blue and muckraker to summon apollousa. if you activated spright starter on your opponents turn before or are able to get two more bodies on the field before linking, you can keep muckraker and just use evil blue and the other two monsters you summoned for even more negates and higher ATK. then, use evil pink's effect to reborn evil blue, popping a card. this triggers abom to pop another card. by now, you've potentially popped five or so of your opponents cards, leaving their field pretty empty and them wide open for a brutal battle phase.

2.) using both evil twins, link into trouble sunny. trouble sunny is not only a 3300 beatstick, but it can split off back into the evil twins any time you want. and it just so happens that we can get two more attacks in during the battle phase if we activate trouble sunny after it attacks. 

3.) now, with abom, apollousa, trouble sunny, and potentially muckraker, we have anywhere from 10k-11k damage we can do in total during battle, and--although completely optional--spright gamma burst, if you have it, gives 1400 bonus ATK to all your level/rank/link-2 monsters. you would want to use gamma burst after your trouble sunny splits, so your evil twins can get the buff. now, if you haven't fallen victim to ash, nib, imperm, ogre, belle, veiler, droplet, tactics, called by, d shifter, super poly, or the wrath of god himself, this should be game. if not, good luck soldier. o7

COMBOING WITH FEWER CARDS

it is possible to get the same board as above with three bodies on the field instead of four or five. this works with a live-twin opening, but it's reliant on masquerena resolving on your opponent's turn which can be risky. this is the case bc sprights lock you into level 2's, and twins lock you into fiends. this usually means the most offensive action you can take this way on your turn is popping a card with evil blue. but i suppose if youre able to get carrot on the field before activating masquerena, getting her to resolve would be easier since carrot is an omni-negate.

1.) if possible, open with your live-twin combo until you end with three bodies. 

2.) xyz summon gigantic spright using two bodies. whatever your three bodies are during this combo, leaving one of the twins on field is mandatory.

3.) activate gigantic spright by removing the opposite twin as material. summon spright blue.

4.) activate spright blue's trigger effect to add spright jet to hand. special summon spright jet and activate its trigger effect to add spright starter to hand. 

5.) use spright starter to summon another spright, preferably carrot in case an emergency negate is needed. 

6.) use spright blue and spright jet to link into masquerena. then, use gigantic spright and your twin to link into the corresponding evil twin.

7.) activate your evil twin to reborn your opposite live-twin. then, link into the opposite evil twin. 

8.) don't activate your second evil twin's reborn effect just yet. use it and your last spright on the field to link into muckraker. then, use muckraker to reborn your second evil twin. NOW, you can activate it to reborn your first evil twin. your end board should be masquerena, muckraker, and both evil twins. on your opponent's turn, activate masquerena to link into unchained abomination with her and evil twin blue. then, reborn blue with pink and start popping cards.

if you are only able to open with two live-twins, link climb into the evil twins into trouble sunny. if you only open with sprights, xyz summon gigantic spright and summon whatever you can with blue, jet, and starter. then link into anything like s:p little knight or something.

GOING SECOND

going second with any deck really is more difficult than winning the lottery, and sadly, this deck is no different. however, there are some alternative combo lines we can do with limited cards on the field if need be. you can do your best to end on abom like the previous combo if you want, but since we already covered that, let's talk about this deck's other boss monsters: mekk-knight crusadia avramax and underworld goddess of the closed world. yeah, once again, this deck is great at abusing generic links.

i would just be repeating myself if i did a step-by-step on how to climb with this deck, so just know that, if possible, you'll want to use masquerena and another link-2 to summon avramax. this should be able to be done with four bodies. with masquerena, avramax will not only be immune to targeted effects but won't be destroyed by non-targeting destruction effects, as well. also, avramax's effect allows him to beat over any special summoned monster in the game that he's in battle with. the only way your opponent should be able to get rid of avramax is by tributing him with something like a kaiju or by using him as material for something like underworld goddess. 

moon and underworld goddess should be able to be climbed into with the three-body combo shown earlier. this is also something that would rely on masquerena resolving. however, with four bodies, this should be doable on your own turn. 

 as for keeping your own sanity long enough to actually resolve a combo going second, 3x triple tactics talent and 3x forbidden droplet are, in my opinion, a must. i have lost count how many times these cards have kept me able to play the game. after a negate that walls off a combo, using ttt to take control of an opponent's monster to use a material is incredibly useful. droplet also is really good at doing droplet things. 

 SIDE DECK AND TECH CARDS

so, there is a lot of room for variety here in the way one can build a live-twin deck. a lot of archetypal card choices are honestly up to personal preference. i'll try to explain what cards you should probably be subbing out when siding.

the evil twins effect monster is for when you need a giga-beatstick bc it comes out on the field with 4400 ATK. if running this card, i strongly recommend siding in a second trouble sunny, as well. this is bc to get the evil twins card on the field, you first banish trouble sunny to send it to the graveyard and pop a card. you can then use your individual evil twin links on the field that were left by trouble sunny splitting to summon the evil twins effect monster. it also has an effect where on summon, your opponent has to obliterate cards on their field until they only have three, but i rarely see that effect coming in clutch over an evenly matched instead. also, i would replace zeus or moon for the second trouble sunny.

transcode talker is for when you need target immunity on your cards, which is nice. what REALLY makes transcode talker nice, tho, is he can reborn masquerena 

knightmare gryphon is a really good stun for this deck bc it is a fiend monster, so when you are fiend-locked by evil twins or muckraker, gryphon is always an option. shutting down your opponent's special summoned monsters' effects is also wonderful, especially if you get gryphon out going first. 

once again, zeus or moon are good to sub out for these. subbing out apollousa for gryphon is also a fine choice since they both do effect negation.

meowmine and saambell are great cards to add to the deck if you want even more bodies and extenders.

meowmine also has a very nice effect of bouncing a card your opponent controls by banishing itself from either your hand OR graveyard. that means you can special summon her to extend your link climbing OR use her a handtrap.

saambell is also good if you are running 2 or 3 copies of frost and treat for whatever reason. maybe in a pure live-twin deck without the spright engine bc saambell at 3x would help prevent bricks. this is more of a fun one.

evil twin present is a free snatch steal in-archetype. the evil twins already respawn each other, so all you would need to do after swapping monsters is destroy your opponent's newly fashioned evil twin and reborn it with the one you still control. 

ghost ogre is also a nice hand trap to run at 3x if you like it bc of where it pops a card, it can trigger unchained abomination.

for either of these, i would suggest swapping out your 3x secret passwords for them. or 2x secret password and 1x live-twin ki-sikil. secret password is there for consistency, but at the end of the day, i would say it's the most replaceable playset in this deck.

something incredibly funny is running secret village at 3x and running any easy-to-summon spellcaster like dharc and locking out your opponent from using spell cards. getting dharc out instead of muckraker would be the way to do it. yeah, not much else to it. just a really funny floodgate. especially funny if your dharc gets deleted, and then YOU can't use spells anymore. ideally, you would have a card on the field that prevents him from being attacked like avramax and a card that prevents him from being targeted or destroyed like transcode talker or masquerena. this is WAYYY easier to do with spright elf, but sadly that card is forbidden.

there's also a burn variant that's playable. lil-la rap makes it so when you reborn anything from the grave (usually an evil twin summoning the other evil twin), your opponent takes 1000 damage. other typical burn cards like lava golem work well, too. lava golem specifically for board removal is nice. also, anything you special summon to their field can be beat over by avramax.

i know what you're thinking: what in the actual world is this random abyss actor card doing here. well, it works as pretty much the only card that can trigger yama in the grave to special summon and abominable unchained soul to summon itself from hand as well. for more information on how the unchained engine works in a live-twin deck, i strongly recommend checking out a master duel player named Saucy Senpai. they are consistently master rank with live-twin and have many live-twin decklists on masterduelmeta and several replays available in-game showing how they use it. they also reply to comments on their decklists often.

as for fiendsmith, although this is a TCG friendly decklist, i admittedly am a master duel slob, so i have no experience with this archetype at all. however, i strongly recommend BubblyBoii on youtube as they are a fellow live-twin lover who experiments with different engines in live-twin, including fiendsmith. i would say this is the go-to place to learn about that synergy.

anyways, thank you for checking out my decklist for live-twin ~!!! i know it's quite the odd flex, but this decklist is where i've landed myself after playing live-twin for several hundred hours, and the only complaint i have with it is the same complaint i have with any other deck: pleasegoddontmakemegoseconditisinsufferable teehee. <3 also, this deck is wayyyy better with spright elf as it deletes any need for transcodetalker and 2 copies of muckraker. muckraker is still good for getting back abom but MANNNNNNN i wish spright elf were legal >_< but whatever, i guess >_> not like i play this game anywhere else but master duel anyway, so i guess it doesn't matter (it matters just a little i really like spright elf :3) but yeah, thank you !!! i hope you like it !!! if you have anything to add, please comment !! i promise i'll read it <3 bye-bye ~~~!!!!

Rafael was the first character who was able to beat Yami Yugi fairly.

His deck was based on the guardian archetype where you need equip spells on field to summon your monsters.

The problem with his deck is that it hasn't good support at all.

That's why I use some very strong equip cards of his archetype + Guardian Eatos his boss monster.

I don't really like the way I've build this deck at all, but I cannot find a better way that's simple enough for you to follow.

I've found a player using the infernoid archetype for both Eatos and Guardian Dreadscythe but It feels so strong and unfair for me, even versus CPU/PC/BOT. Here is his approach: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L2DUzscMDA0&list=WL&index=21

And I really wanna say a big WELL DONE to him.

Let's return to my deck now! There are many Boss monsters in the Extra Deck and with the help of equip spells (that are very easy to search), you can always do heavy damage to your opponent. Many of these Boss monsters reminds me of Rafaels cards as well.

I was able to beat some of the strongest characters in offline mode (Legacy of the Duelist: Link Evolution) with such a custom and experimental deck like this without great Guardian supportive cards. You might dislike it, but don't forget that most of these cards exist in his ERA (OG yugioh) and it still feels competitive enough in story mode for example.

I’m pretty sure that the phrase “using T.G. cards to turbo into Elemental Grace Doriado in order to do Prediction Princess combos” warrants a wellness check in most cases, but here we are. We are looking at Elemental Grace Doriado which is a Level 9 LIGHT Spellcaster monster with 0 ATK/DEF. She cannot be Normal Summoned or set and MUST be Special Summoned from your hand by having 6 or more monsters with different Attributes in the GYs. She gains ATK/DEF equal to the number of different Attributes in the GYs x500. And when your opponent could Special Summon a monster(s), she can Quick Effect banish 3 monsters from your GY to negate the Summon and destroy those monsters and this effect is not once per turn. Now, the thing about Elemental Grace Doriado is that she is very hard to Summon. First, you need to have her in hand. And second, you need to have 6 different Attributes of monster in GY. Yes, you can count the monster Attributes in your opponent’s GY, but relying on your opponent so that you can start your plays is something that you do not want to do in this game. The only benefit to actually summoning her is having access to some number of Special Summon negates which is alright for the most part. When you compare her to a card like D/D/D Wave High King Caesar, who is much easier to Summon thanks to the Fiendsmith cards, the most obvious difference is their Summoning Requirements and that basically creates a massive gap between the two. I would rather have access to a very easy to Summon Rank 6 monster that requires 2 Fiends for 2 Solemn Warning-esque effects rather than having to get 6 different Attributes into the GY and draw a near-unsearchable monster who gives at the very least 2 Special Summon negates. Most of the time when you are Summoning Doriado, the amount of resources and effort you have to put into Summoning her prevent you from having anything else on your field to give her protection or act as other forms of interaction. However, we are sadly not going to be keeping her on the field as we are just going to be using her as Rank 9 material and casting her away forever. The biggest reason for this is because she MUST be Special Summoned via her own Summoning Condition. She cannot be Summoned back from GY even after you have correctly Summoned her already. And with our combo to get her out requiring us to play a lot of Spell/Traps in the Deck, we are limited on the number of monsters we are allowed to play, preventing us from having say Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag in the Deck to potentially have a different Level 9 to use as Xyz Material over Doriado. So why are we using the T.G. monsters? This Deck aims to Synchro Summon Ib the World Chalice Justiciar to search for World Legacy Monstrosity before Synchro Summoning into Rciela, Sinister Soul of the White Forest to search for Doriado. We need some number of Level 1 monsters to do that, and considering that T.G. has a lot of Level 1 monsters of varying Attributes, it is perfect for this Deck. Granted, we are playing the Diabellstar package simply because it allows very easy access to the entire T.G. line we are aiming for and because weaving her into the combo means that we can possibly also end on a Level 10 Synchro Monster in addition to our Prediction Princess board while also having had enough Attributes in GY for Doriado. We do not necessarily need Diabellstar, but it is still really good to be playing her. All you need is Diabellstar, a discard, a Spell/Trap, and a T.G. non-Tuner. Discard a card to Summon Diabellstar the Black Witch and she triggers on Summon to set Original Sinful Spoils - Snake-Eye from Deck. Activate it sending her to GY to Special Summon T.G. Rocket Salamander from Deck. Salamander Tributes itself to Special Summon T.G. Screw Serpent from Deck who triggers on Summon to bring back Salamander from GY. Let’s say the non-Tuner T.G. you have in hand is another copy of Rocket Salamander. Normal Summon it since we haven’t normaled yet. Synchro Screw Serpent and one of the Salamanders into Ib the World Chalice Justiciar. Ib searches for World Legacy Monstrosity on Synchro Summon. Next, Synchro Ib and your other Rocket Salamander into Rciela, Sinister Soul of the White Forest. Chain Link 1 Rciela discarding a Spell/Trap (DO NOT DISCARD MONSTROSITY, Chain Link 2 Ib in GY. The Chain resolves backwards, so Ib Special Summons Beckoned by the World Chalice from Deck and Rciela adds Elemental Grace Doriado from Deck to hand. We now need a WIND monster, so we will be Linking off Beckoned for Imduk the World Chalice Guardragon. Next, Link both Imduk and Rciela into Sky Striker Ace - Camellia. Now, you have the DARK Diabellstar the Black Witch, the LIGHT Rciela, Sinister Soul of the White Forest, the EARTH Beckoned by the World Chalice, the FIRE T.G. Rocket Salamander, the WATER Ib the World Chalice Justiciar/T.G. Screw Serpent, and the WIND Imduk the World Chalice Guardragon in GY. Special Summon Elemental Grace Doriado from your hand and proceed to activate Monstrosity targeting it to Special Summon Prediction Princess Bibliomuse and Deus-X Krawler from Deck. Now, say goodbye to her as we use both her and Deus-X to make Mereologic Aggregator to transition into full Prediction Princess combo. If you don’t have Diabellstar, you just need T.G. Rocket Salamander, a non-Tuner T.G. monster, and a Spell/Trap to discard. You do the exact same combo, but when you get to Camellia, Link her off for any Link-1 Sky Striker Monster to put her in the GY as your DARK monster. This Deck is surprisingly consistent. It’s a shame Baronne is banned since we could’ve used it as part of our endboard, but what we have here is still very solid.

Main Deck: 1 Beckoned by the World Chalice. There are other ways to get an EARTH in GY for Doriado which is to play Sky Striker Ace - Kaina to Link into using Camellia and proceeding to Link her off for another Link-1 Sky Striker monster. But, you still need to Summon a monster off of Ib because you need to put Rciela into GY by Linking it off with another monster into a Link-2. And a Normal Monster is best for this because we can use it to make Imduk for our WIND in case we do not draw Booster Raptor. 2 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei can Quick Effect flip a monster on field face-up or face-down and she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down during your End Phase. We are only playing 2 of her because we need to find a way to cut down on our monster count to ensure drawing a Spell/Trap for Rciela’s effect, and so Tarotrei my first choice to cut down by 1 copy. Tarotreith must either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei's effect in the End Phase. Her Flip Effect Special Summons a Flip Monster from your Deck face-downn and she can also Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back face-down after being Tributed and sent there. Her Flip Effect adds a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand and while she is face-up on the field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s card effects. 2 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent's side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute. 1 Divine Grace Doriado. 3 Diabellstar the Black Witch. You can Special Summon her from your hand by sending a card from your hand or field to the GY and on Normal or Special Summon, she can set a Sinful Spoils Spell/Trap from Deck. That’s pretty much all that we are using her for. The main card we are setting off of her is Original Sinful Spoils - Snake-Eye which we are only playing a single copy of. Even if you do draw it, you can still set WANTED: Seeker of Sinful Spoils from Deck with Diabellstar’s effect and that’s still really good as you can send it from field to GY for Rciela’s effect. For the T.G. monsters, we are playing 2 T.G. Screw Serpent, 3 T.G. Rocket Salamander, and 3 T.G. Booster Raptor. Screw Serpent targets a Level 4 or lower T.G. monster in your GY except for itself on Normal or Special Summon and Special Summons it. Rocket Salamander Tributes a T.G. monster to Special Summon a T.G. monster from your Deck with a different original name than the Tributed monster’s. And Booster Raptor can Special Summon itself from your hand if you control a T.G. monster and it is a WIND for Doriado. Notably, it is a Level 1 non-Tuner T.G.. We need Level 1 non-Tuners so that we can Synchro it and Ib into Rciela. That means that we should not be playing cards like T.G. Gear Zombie, T.G. Cyber Magician, or T.G. Tank Grub. You could play T.G. Drill Fish, but I would like to keep the monster count down. 

Spell/Traps: 1 Instant Fusion for Master of Ham. 3 Pot of Prosperity. 1 Original Sinful Spoils - Snake-Eye which sends 1 other card you control to GY to Special Summon a Level 1 FIRE monster from your hand or Deck. It gets you Rocket Salamander, so what more can you ask for? 3 WANTED: Seeker of Sinful Spoils which adds a Diabellstar monster from Deck or GY to your hand and you can banish it from GY and target a Sinful Spoils Spell/Trap that’s banished or in GY except for another copy of WANTED and place it on the bottom of the Deck to draw 1 card. 1 World Legacy Monstrosity which either Special Summons a Level 9 monster from hand or targets a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different Type and Attribute but with different names. 1 World Legacy Succession which targets a monster in your GY and Special Summons it to Linkpoint. 3 T.G. Limiter Removal which discards a card to add 2 T.G. monsters with different names from your Deck to your hand which is just crazy. Notice that we are not playing T.G. All Clear that card does literally nothing in this Deck. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which can Ritual Summon a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess monster from Deck face-down. 3 Infinite Impermanence. 

Extra Deck: 1 Master of Ham which Special Summons a Flip Monster from hand or Deck face-down on Fusion Summon. 1 Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying which is just a Synchro 10 we can go into if we want (Baronne is banned). 1 Rciela, Sinister Soul of the White Forest who sends a Spell/Trap from hand/field to GY on Special Summon to add a White Forest card or 1 LIGHT Spellcaster monster from Deck to hand. This is how we are searching for Doriado. Even if we do draw her in our opener, we still need to make Rciela to put a LIGHT in our GY. 1 Ib the World Chalice Justiciar which adds a World Legacy card from Deck to hand on Synchro Summon and floats into a World Chalice monster when sent from field to GY. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which searches for a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell if sent to the GY. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 S:P Little Knight, 1 Sky Striker Ace - Camellia, 1 Imduk the World Chalice Guardragon, 1 Gravity Controller, and 1 Sky Striker Ace - Hayate (you can play any Link-1 Sky Striker monster). 

Side Deck: 3 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Kashtira Fenrir, 3 Dark Ruler No More, 1 Harpie’s Feather Duster, 2 Lightning Storm, and 3 Evenly Matched.

Welcome to my build of Libromancers! 

-

I'll be quite honest, I crafted nearly every piece for this only to dismantle it later before the Origin Story support dropped. NEEDLESS TO SAY, it was worth crafting twice (also, I was still reintroducing myself to the game as a whole and this particular Ritual strategy was way beyond my skill level initially.) 

Regardless, I absolutely love this deck as it allows you to pump out some very strong threats for a game that is pushing past a couple turns. 

-  

Libromancers is a very flexible Ritual-oriented archetype that can mesh well with Cyberse-Link, Floodgates and Combo (depending on what you're going for.) Only downside is that your endboard will be entirely dependent on what you have available in-hand.

Some games you'll end on 4 to 6 negates (no seriously) and others will quite literally just be a Full-Powered Fireburst*** 
Both are equally as compelling strategies around Gold/Plat/Early Diamond. 

- 

Ideally, your key players are going to be [Libromancer Doombroker] and [Libromancer Fireburst], the bosses of the deck, so to speak. 

Doombroker has the ability to attack your opponent directly, spin a card back into the hand, set Libromancer Traps and has a very promising statblock once [Libromancer Origin Story] is on the field. It's a phenomenal card that can accomplish so much in a single turn while also providing the ability to do it again and again thanks to it's Effect Monster parent card [Libromancer Agent] which has the ability to return any Libromancer card back to the hand. Spells and Traps, however, come at a cost of returning 1 card to the Deck.

Fireburst is a much more unique card in that it's quite literally the Father of all Beatsticks. 

*** The trick that often gets overlooked is the combination of using [Libromancer Firestarter] and [Libromancer Bonded]. 
How it works is you summon Firestarter and use Bonded to summon Fireburst. Fireburst has battle destruction immunity (so long as it's summoned using at least 1 monster on the field, same as the other Libro Rituals), but using Bonded as opposed to the Field Spell and Firestarter as a Tribute, per Bonded, you grant Destruction AND Banish immunity. Period. That means, no Evenly, no Fenrir, no Raigeki, etc. The only out would be a spin back to the hand/deck or a Kaiju/Sphere. 

It's not as attractive as having several negates, but the amount of games I've had where my opponent would have to expend double the amount of resources just to out this one card was always something to behold. Doubly so considering you'll end up dismantling their board as you'll most likely run into another Origin Story which would put Fireburst at a whopping 4500 ATK, and that's not including it's other ability that can grant it another 200 ATK per banishing a Ritual Monster from the grave (ya know, just in case.)  It's a really funny card to say the least. 

- 

Alas, you have your extenders that will carry you into your Extra Deck: [Diviner of the Herald] being your key in all this, but also searchable through [Cyber Angel Benten] so you're not having to go crazy trying to toolbox it. 

Play around with the Extra Deck slots if you'd like.

I particularly like this line-up as it's geared more toward a Mid-Range approach. There will always be some kind of a threat on the board assuming you're not getting wiped Turn 1. My strategy with this was to create a contest of attrition as sometimes you don't exactly have all the pieces you need when you (desperately) need them. 

- 

Most I've ever accomplished in a single turn was [Herald of the Arc Light], [Baronne de Fleur]. [Libromancer Doombroker] (with the in-archetype Negate/Monster Steal set), [Libromancer Magigirl] (Quick-Play Ritual Summon) into [Libromancer Mystigirl] (a Monster Negate that reduces ATK to 0), an Ash in hand and Called By set. 

Granted, absolutely uninterrupted god hand, but yeah... this deck can do a lot. 

- 

Lastly, I've included alternative strategies in the Sideboard, specifically the addition of Vanity's Ruler and Chaos Hunter. 

Back in Kashtira format, these two were my lifelines. Ruler being searchable off Benten was a game changer. 9/10 Times, you'll have two monsters on the field to Tribute and if you have Chaos in hand then it's doubly frustrating for your opponent as their only answers come in the form of a board wipe. 

Either way, it's burning your opponent's resources until you can pop off. To which, they're expending that much gas to get anything off the board while you're busy setting up a fortress of negates and responses. 

- 

In conclusion, this Deck is crazy fun. Handtraps kind of dead a lot of the lines, but you have a good number of searchers to get to some kind of strategy. However, when it gets going, it's kinda hard for it to stop cascading into every crevice of your strategies. 

-

Welcome to my Suship build! 

- 

Okay, I know what you're thinking: "Why are there Floodgates in an XYZ spam deck."
And my answer to that is... the current format called for it. 

That said, I added a Synchro line in the Sidedeck that I'll go into briefly, but for now... Suships. 

- 

Suships are your run-of-the-mill Rank 4 XYZ spam, only better because it's literally sushi in the form of a battleship... that can OTK. 

Star players being literally all of the ships, it's not difficult in the slightest to bring out the fleet turn 1. If anything, it's going to be your primary endboard. 

Here's the breakdown: 

[Gunkan Suship Shirauo-class Carrier] acts as your searcher for any of the Suship Spell/Traps. Gonna be completely honest, the only ones you'll be looking for are most likely going to be the Field Spell or the Trap. However, using Shari as a material nets you a draw, like the other Suships as well, but in this case it's definitely worth going +2 if you want a decent follow-up. Also, Carrier grants immunity to your Suship XYZ monsters so long as there is ANY Field Spell online (imagine the mental gymnastics your opponents face deciding on if they really need that Spell out) as well as a slight boost in ATK to any Suship XYZ on the field based on their DEF. 

One thing to note is that this effect stacks. So, having 3 Carriers on the field is actually a viable strategy considering your XYZ monsters are gonna be HUGE. Pair that with their effects and... well... you'll see what I mean. 

[Gunkan Suship Ikura-class Dreadnought] acts as your beatstick. Same deal as all the other ships, making it with the corresponding materials will allow this monster to attack twice in a single Battle Phase and also net you 1 draw. However, it has a fun ability that allows this card to destroy 1 card on the field so long as any of your ships inflict damage. Also stackable! I know! 

[Gunkan Suship Uni-class Super Dreadnought] acts as your negate. This one is a little specific though. As usual, making it with the corresponding materials will net you 1 draw and allow for this card to attack your opponent directly. As for the negate, it's really strong, but easily counterable. You're granted 1 face-up card negate per Suship XYZ monster you have on the field. It is an Omni-Negate that persists even if Super Dreadnought isn't on the field. So deliciously annoying, lol. Only caveat is that you can freely negate during the Main Phase of your turn and only during the Battle Phase of your opponent's. 

With their powers combined, you have a near-indestructible armada of culinary masterpieces that can render a board virtually useless assuming you're timing the effects correctly. In that, I mean sometimes you'll catch an Ash or Veiler before you can get your full board going, which is fine. All that matters is getting your ships on the field and causing some serious damage. 

If all else fails, you have some choice picks for alternative XYZ monsters. All of which are meant to be equally as annoying. 

Notable mentions are:
[Number F0: Utopic Draco Future] 
[Time Thief Redoer]
[Tornado Dragon] 

And of course, you have the Link lines which are more insurance than anything else. 

If you can manage getting both [Promethean Princess] and [Overlay Network] on the board at the same time, you've pretty much won. Both cards will ensure that there won't be a single card you won't be able to access in the Extra. 

- 

Lastly, to briefly go over the Sideboard. I discovered some interesting Synchro tech that made for some interesting games. 

Using Ringowurm as your primary Tuner and being able to, essentially, Special or Normal Summon the Shari Normal Monster, you get a free special summon from the hand into a quick Level 6 Synchro extender. 

[Revolution Synchron] can grant you a free [Clear Wing Synchro Dragon] and then a great follow-up into [Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon] or any other Level 10 Synchro you might have in your arsenal.

[Psychic End Punisher] also makes for a choice pick here.

Regardless, definitely give it a shot if you're not looking into dragging out games for 20 turns with the initial Floodgate strategy. 

- 

In conclusion, this is my second favorite archetype of all time and I'm so glad that it has got some attention over the last couple of XYZ events. It's definitely a super-budget friendly deck where you could throw literally anything at the wall and it'll stick 8/10 times. 

So, start your new career and become a Suship Chef today! 

-

deck_name: Seto Kaiba Manga Battle City+ Deck
deck_excerpt: Seto Kaiba Playable Accurate Battle City+ Deck
deck_description:
Kaiba's Manga accurate Battle City deck. There were not enough cards for the deck to be playable using the manga as the only source, so I supplimented the deck with the monsters from the anime below:

Judge Man - Duelist Kingdom / Waking the Dragons

La-Jinn - Duelist Kingdom

Ancient Lamp - Duelist Kingdom

Spear Dragon - Waking the Dragons

Kaiser Sea Horse - Waking the Dragons

Enraged Battle Ox - Takes the place of Battle Ox from Duelist Kingdom, fits the deck much better

Pitch-Dark Dragon - Waking the Dragons

Crush Card Virus - Duelist Kingdom / Waking the Dragons

Thunder Dragons didn't make the cut as it weakened the deck too much.


This deck was balanced to be at approximately the same power level as my other character decks, make sure to check those out too!

deck_description: The goal of this Yu-Gi-Oh! deck is to utilize Drytron and Icejade cards to protect Vanity’s Ruler. The strategy involves executing a one-card combo with Icejade Aegirine to summon a Level 10 Icejade Synchro monster, which helps defend Vanity’s Ruler. This deck simplifies the process by requiring the discard of a Water monster. By using Drytron Thuban, you can search for a Water Ritual monster and add it to your hand, enabling the combo to work effectively. If you have any ideas on how to improve either this deck or the previous one, I would appreciate your suggestions.This deck was created to gauge which build might be more effective. I have a Drytron-Crystron-Icejade deck on my profile, but I've made some edits and would appreciate any tips on how to improve it. If you have suggestions for making it better, I’d love to hear them!

O Structure Deck: Yugi Edition (2001) é um baralho pré-construído do famoso jogo de cartas Yu-Gi-Oh!, lançado no Japão em 28 de junho de 2001. Este deck marca o início da série de Structure Decks no jogo oficial de cartas (OCG) e é inspirado nas cartas utilizadas por Yugi Muto, um dos personagens centrais do anime e mangá Yu-Gi-Oh!.

Composto por 56 cartas, o deck inclui duas cartas novas: "Swift Gaia the Fierce Knight" e "Obnoxious Celtic Guard". A carta de capa do baralho é "Archfiend of Gilfer", mas versões alternativas apresentam "Dark Magician Girl" e "Obnoxious Celtic Guard" como destaque.

Entre as cartas notáveis do deck, as ultra raras "Swift Gaia the Fierce Knight" e "Obnoxious Celtic Guard" se destacam, acompanhadas pela super rara "Dark Magician Girl". Além disso, o deck inclui diversas cartas comuns, mas icônicas, como "Dark Magician", "Kuriboh", "Buster Blader", e "Monster Reborn".

Este deck é uma excelente escolha para os fãs do personagem Yugi e para aqueles que desejam reviver os emocionantes duelos clássicos do anime. E você, já teve a oportunidade de jogar com algum deck de Yu-Gi-Oh!?

O Structure Deck: Jonouchi Edition (2001), conhecido também como Structure Deck: Joey, é um baralho pré-construído do jogo de cartas Yu-Gi-Oh!, lançado no Japão em 25 de outubro de 2001. Este deck é o segundo da série de Structure Decks do jogo oficial de cartas (OCG), sucedendo o Structure Deck: Yugi.

Composto por 56 cartas, o deck inclui várias cartas icônicas usadas por Joey Wheeler (Jonouchi) no anime, como o Red-Eyes Black Dragon, Jinzo, Time Wizard, e introduz duas novas cartas: Luminous Soldier e Command Knight. Além dessas, o baralho conta com uma variedade de monstros, magias e armadilhas que capturam o estilo de jogo característico de Jonouchi, refletindo sua estratégia e personalidade dentro do universo de Yu-Gi-Oh!.

O *Structure Deck: Kaiba Edition* é uma das edições mais icônicas lançadas na série de decks estruturados do jogo de cartas colecionáveis *Yu-Gi-Oh!*. Inspirado no lendário duelista Seto Kaiba, esse deck reflete o poder e a estratégia do personagem, oferecendo aos jogadores uma coleção de cartas que giram em torno do Dragão Branco de Olhos Azuis e outras criaturas poderosas associadas a ele.

Desde o seu lançamento, o *Structure Deck: Kaiba Edition* se destacou por sua combinação de força bruta e táticas de controle. O deck é construído em torno de uma sinergia que permite ao jogador invocar rapidamente monstros de alto ataque, ao mesmo tempo em que oferece opções para neutralizar as jogadas do oponente. Cartas como *Opressão Imperial* e *Raio de Destruição* adicionam uma camada estratégica, permitindo que os duelistas dominem o campo e mantenham o controle do jogo.

Além disso, o *Structure Deck: Kaiba Edition* não só homenageia o personagem icônico da série, mas também se tornou uma base sólida para jogadores que desejam construir um deck competitivo. Combinando o clássico poder do Dragão Branco de Olhos Azuis com novas cartas e estratégias, este deck continua a ser uma escolha popular entre veteranos e novatos no jogo.

Em resumo, o *Structure Deck: Kaiba Edition* representa uma fusão entre a nostalgia e a eficácia moderna, capturando a essência do personagem Seto Kaiba e proporcionando uma experiência de duelo intensa e dominadora.

deck_name: Structure Deck: Pegasus J. Crawford Edition (2002)
deck_excerpt: Structure Deck: Pegasus J. Crawford Edition (2002)
deck_description:
O "Structure Deck: Pegasus J. Crawford Edition" foi lançado em 2002 como parte da série de decks estruturados do jogo de cartas Yu-Gi-Oh!. Este deck é inspirado no personagem Maximillion Pegasus, conhecido no anime por ser o criador do jogo de cartas Duel Monsters e o principal antagonista do primeiro arco da série. 

O deck foi projetado para refletir o estilo de jogo e as estratégias utilizadas por Pegasus no anime, focando principalmente em monstros Toon e cartas relacionadas a essa temática. Monstros Toon são uma característica marcante do deck, proporcionando uma jogabilidade única, já que esses monstros têm habilidades especiais, como a capacidade de atacar diretamente os pontos de vida do oponente. 

Além dos monstros Toon, o deck também inclui cartas mágicas e armadilhas que complementam a estratégia de Pegasus, como "Toon World", uma carta chave que permite a invocação de monstros Toon. Essa edição do deck oferece uma introdução temática para os jogadores que desejam experimentar o estilo de jogo de Pegasus, ao mesmo tempo que reforça as mecânicas específicas associadas ao universo dos monstros Toon.

O "Structure Deck: Pegasus J. Crawford Edition" é uma peça significativa na história de Yu-Gi-Oh!, não apenas por representar um personagem icônico, mas também por proporcionar uma experiência de jogo imersiva que conecta os fãs ao mundo do anime. É uma escolha popular entre os jogadores que apreciam a nostalgia e a complexidade das estratégias baseadas em cartas temáticas.

O *Structure Deck: Jonouchi Edition Volume 2* é uma coleção de cartas lançada em 2003 como parte da série de decks estruturados de Yu-Gi-Oh!. Esse deck é uma homenagem ao personagem Katsuya Jonouchi, conhecido como Joey Wheeler na versão ocidental do anime. O produto foi desenvolvido para proporcionar aos fãs uma experiência nostálgica, permitindo-lhes reviver as estratégias e o estilo de jogo característicos do personagem.

O *Structure Deck* inclui uma seleção cuidadosa de cartas que refletem o estilo de duelo de Jonouchi, focando em monstros de alta força de ataque e estratégias de combate direto. Entre as cartas principais estão o *Dragão Negro de Olhos Vermelhos* e o *Dragão das Trevas de Metal Vermelho*, dois dos monstros mais icônicos associados ao duelista. Além disso, o deck contém diversas cartas de suporte que ajudam a fortalecer o poder de ataque dos monstros e a manter o controle do campo de batalha.

Lançado durante o auge da popularidade de Yu-Gi-Oh!, o *Jonouchi Edition Volume 2* foi amplamente aceito tanto por novos jogadores quanto por colecionadores, servindo como uma ponte entre a série animada e o jogo de cartas colecionáveis. Sua composição equilibrada permite que jogadores iniciantes possam competir de forma eficaz, enquanto os duelistas mais experientes podem utilizá-lo como base para construir estratégias mais complexas.

Em resumo, o *Structure Deck: Jonouchi Edition Volume 2* é uma representação icônica do personagem Jonouchi dentro do universo de Yu-Gi-Oh!, capturando a essência de seu estilo de duelo e oferecendo aos jogadores uma peça valiosa tanto para duelos quanto para coleções.
Tribute

**Structure Deck: Kaiba Edition Volume 2 (2003)**

Lançado em 2003, o **Structure Deck: Kaiba Edition Volume 2** é um dos produtos mais emblemáticos da linha de decks estruturados do jogo **Yu-Gi-Oh!**. Inspirado no icônico personagem **Seto Kaiba**, este deck é uma continuação do sucesso do primeiro volume, trazendo aos duelistas uma nova oportunidade de explorar a estratégia e o poder do rival de **Yugi Muto**.

Este deck é composto por uma seleção de cartas que reflete o estilo de jogo agressivo e controlado de **Kaiba**, com destaque para os dragões poderosos e cartas de suporte que potencializam suas estratégias. O **Dragão Branco de Olhos Azuis**, carta assinatura de Kaiba, é o pilar central do deck, representando o ápice do poder e da ferocidade que o personagem tanto valoriza. Além disso, cartas como **Caveira Convocada** e **Guerreiro X-Head Canon** reforçam o foco em monstros fortes e difíceis de derrotar.

Outro aspecto notável deste deck é a inclusão de cartas mágicas e armadilhas que permitem ao duelista manter o controle do campo, anulando as estratégias do oponente e criando oportunidades para ataques devastadores. **Controle Mental** e **Força do Espelho** são exemplos de cartas que desempenham um papel crucial na estratégia defensiva e ofensiva de Kaiba, refletindo sua abordagem meticulosa e calculada nos duelos.

O **Structure Deck: Kaiba Edition Volume 2** não apenas oferece aos fãs a chance de vivenciar a experiência de jogar como um dos personagens mais icônicos do universo de **Yu-Gi-Oh!**, mas também serve como uma excelente base para iniciantes e veteranos que desejam construir um deck poderoso e temático. Este produto é uma homenagem ao legado de **Seto Kaiba**, capturando a essência de sua personalidade e estilo de duelo em cada carta.

Assim, o **Structure Deck: Kaiba Edition Volume 2** permanece como um item de colecionador e uma ferramenta valiosa para aqueles que desejam dominar o jogo com a mesma determinação e ambição que definem **Seto Kaiba**.
Gimmick Puppet

O **Structure Deck: Marik Edition**, lançado em 2004, é um produto icônico da série de cartas colecionáveis Yu-Gi-Oh!. Este deck é centrado no vilão Marik Ishtar, um dos antagonistas principais da saga, e oferece uma coleção de cartas que refletem seu estilo de jogo e estratégias sombrias.

O deck é composto por 40 cartas, sendo muitas delas focadas em monstros do tipo Zumbi e na temática de controle mental e manipulação, características marcantes do personagem Marik. Entre as cartas mais notáveis, destaca-se o monstro de efeito "O Dragão Alado de Rá", uma das três cartas divinas que desempenha um papel crucial na série. Esta carta simboliza o poder devastador que Marik busca liberar durante suas batalhas.

Além disso, o deck inclui cartas de armadilha e magia que complementam as estratégias de Marik, como "O Controle da Mente" e "A Armadilha de Pesadelo", que são ferramentas eficazes para desestabilizar o oponente e garantir a vitória. Essas cartas permitem ao jogador imitar o estilo de jogo do próprio Marik, caracterizado por sua habilidade de dominar o campo de batalha e virar o jogo a seu favor com movimentos astutos e inesperados.

O **Structure Deck: Marik Edition** foi bem recebido pelos fãs de Yu-Gi-Oh! por oferecer um deck pronto para jogo, que captura a essência de um dos vilões mais memoráveis da série. Ele não apenas oferece uma experiência de jogo única, mas também serve como uma peça de colecionador para os entusiastas do universo Yu-Gi-Oh!. Com sua combinação de cartas poderosas e uma temática sombria, este deck se tornou um marco na história do jogo, sendo lembrado com carinho pelos jogadores e colecionadores até os dias de hoje.

Tenpai deck

The goal of the deck is to summon slifer, however it would be a waste to stop here, the strong engine use in this deck allow you a lot of summon and draw to summon strong monster from your extra deck stop your opponent to play.


There are the steps :

1 - Summon slifer :

   The easiest way to summon slifer is to use his signature trap " the revived sky god ", to use it slifer has to be in GY.
To get slifer in the graveyard there is multiple way, the easiest is to use the fiendsmith engine to XYZ summon beatrice to foolish from the deck, in case slifer is in your hand you can discard it with horus engine," knigthmare gryphon " or " Fiendsmith's Tract ", you can even use " Illusion of chaos " to get slifer back in the deck to foolish it afterward;

Slifer is the deck now you have to set the trap, " lilith, lady of lament " can add it from your deck to your hand, there no real combo to summon her, the best way to use her effect is to normal summon her, summon her from your hand or GY with " tank toy " effect or to use " Tour guide from the underworld " to link summon " Muckracker From the underworld " and summon back lilith to use her effect.
Fiendish Rino Warrior allow you to foolish her so you can once again summon her thank to toy tank or muckracker.

This way you have slifer in graveyard and the revived sky god set, you can use it next turn to get 6 cards in hands and a free slifer.

2 - Build your board :

   As you can see the deck use 5 engine :
-- Horus --
It allow you to get free discard and a lot of summon to access strong control monsters like griphon or apollousa, it can also give you from 1 to 6 draw at once if your opponent try to destroy your cards while "duamutef, Blessing of Horus" is on your side

This engine alse give strong recover for your second turn where this deck shine

--Fiendsmith--
It is essentially use to summon beatrice to foolish slifer, in case you can't get slifer and set the revived sky god this turn you can also summon the D/D/D XYZ monster to negate summons or you can use this engine to destroy card on the board thank to Fiensmith engraver effect

--Unchained--
Also a one esay one card combo engine that can give you free extenders, foolish and summon back lilith or you can use it to remove monster from your opponent side.
Unchained Sharvana is lvl 6 so he can also be used for XYZ summon beatrice or D/D/D with fiendsmith cards.

--Toy--
Used to get easily 3 monster on your side of the field thank to toy box who can set toy tank and soldier who summons themselves back when they are send to GY, tank toy can then tribute himself to summon lvl 6 or lower monster from your hand or GY.

--Dark Magician--
" Illusion of chaos " can add magician soul's and get any card from your hand in the deck, magician soul's is used to combo with toys and draw 2, this way you got 3 special summon and draw 2

Hope you'll like it.

This deck revolves around the Sphinx monsters and their respective trap card, Pyramid of Light . This is based of ACP's original build, which can be found at here.

While I think the build is good, I wanted more options for hard tributing the Sphinx monsters. I cut Goblin Attack Force for Giant Rat - not only does it thin the the deck, but it also works nicely with Beast Soul Swap so you can dodge something like Mirror Force (thus axing your ability to float into another). I added 2x Tribute to the Doomed in the spell lineup, as 7x level 10s can brick really hard and we need an option for dead cards.. I also cut 1x Fake Trap for a Torrential Tribute as Fake Trap is a really bad top deck, and Torrential is just too good not to include.

Other than that, the game plan is simple - stick your Sphinx monsters on board and OTK. They can put out a lot a damage and work nicely with Skill Drain . The side deck is defensive - Sphinx can actually work pretty well with goat control to help stall until you can get all your combo pieces in hand.

Making a wacky deck

**Structure Deck: Dragon's Roar (2004)**

O *Structure Deck: Dragon's Roar*, lançado em 2004, foi um marco significativo na história do jogo de cartas Yu-Gi-Oh!. Como parte da linha de *Structure Decks*, este produto foi projetado para fornecer aos jogadores um deck pronto para jogar, focado em uma estratégia específica, neste caso, a de monstros Dragão. 

Este deck era centrado principalmente no famoso *Dragão Armado LV7*, uma das cartas mais emblemáticas da época, que não apenas servia como a peça central do deck, mas também como uma demonstração da mecânica de evolução, algo inovador para muitos jogadores na época. Além disso, o *Dragon's Roar* trouxe uma série de cartas que auxiliavam na invocação e fortalecimento dos monstros Dragão, tornando o deck altamente sinérgico.

O *Dragon's Roar* era particularmente atraente tanto para jogadores iniciantes quanto para os mais experientes. Para os novos jogadores, ele oferecia uma introdução eficaz ao jogo com uma estratégia poderosa e relativamente fácil de entender. Para os veteranos, o deck apresentava oportunidades para personalização e otimização, com cartas que poderiam ser integradas a decks já existentes.

Além disso, o *Structure Deck: Dragon's Roar* desempenhou um papel importante na popularização de decks temáticos em Yu-Gi-Oh!. A ideia de um deck focado em um tipo específico de monstro ou estratégia foi algo que ganhou muita tração após o lançamento deste produto, influenciando diretamente a direção futura do jogo.

Em resumo, o *Structure Deck: Dragon's Roar* de 2004 não foi apenas um sucesso comercial, mas também uma influência duradoura na comunidade de Yu-Gi-Oh!, definindo tendências e abrindo portas para novos estilos de jogo que continuaram a evoluir ao longo dos anos.

**Yugi's Legendary Decks: Exodia**

O baralho lendário de Yugi Muto é um dos mais icônicos na história do Yu-Gi-Oh!, especialmente pelo seu uso de Exodia, o Proibido. Exodia é uma das cartas mais poderosas e conhecidas do jogo, não apenas pela sua força individual, mas pelo impacto que teve na estratégia de duelos desde a sua introdução. Composto por cinco peças separadas – a cabeça, os dois braços e as duas pernas – Exodia concede ao duelista uma vitória automática se todas as partes estiverem na mão ao mesmo tempo. 

No anime, Yugi Muto utilizou esse baralho para derrotar Seto Kaiba em um dos duelos mais memoráveis da série original. A invocação de Exodia foi um momento marcante que demonstrou a profundidade da estratégia de Yugi e sua habilidade de confiar no coração das cartas. Essa vitória ajudou a solidificar o status lendário de Yugi como um dos melhores duelistas de todos os tempos. 

A estratégia por trás do baralho de Exodia exige paciência e planejamento cuidadoso. O duelista deve focar em proteger suas cartas e acelerar a compra do baralho, utilizando cartas como "Grim Reaper", "Graveyard of the Dead" e "Pot of Greed". A chave é resistir ao ataque do oponente enquanto se tenta completar a mão de Exodia. Esta tática não é apenas um teste de sorte, mas também de habilidade na construção do deck e na tomada de decisões durante o duelo.

O baralho de Exodia é um símbolo de nostalgia para muitos fãs de Yu-Gi-Oh!, representando uma era em que a estratégia e a sorte se combinavam de maneiras emocionantes e inesperadas. Mesmo anos depois de sua primeira aparição, Exodia continua a ser uma força a ser reconhecida, tanto nos duelos quanto na memória coletiva dos fãs.

**Yugi's Legendary Decks: Battle City**

O *Battle City* foi um dos eventos mais marcantes na saga de *Yu-Gi-Oh!* e se destaca especialmente pelas cartas lendárias utilizadas por Yugi Muto. Durante este torneio, Yugi não apenas enfrentou alguns dos duelistas mais fortes do mundo, mas também aprimorou e refinou seu deck, transformando-o em uma verdadeira força a ser reconhecida.

Uma das principais características do deck de Yugi durante o *Battle City* é a inclusão das três Cartas Deus Egípcio: *Slifer, o Dragão do Céu*, *Obelisco, o Atormentador* e *O Dragão Alado de Rá*. Essas cartas são extremamente poderosas e foram fundamentais em diversas batalhas cruciais, simbolizando o ápice do poder e da estratégia de Yugi. Além disso, o deck conta com várias cartas mágicas e armadilhas que desempenham papéis estratégicos importantes, como *Mil Espadas do Corredor das Sombras* e *Soldado de Obsidiana*.

O deck de Yugi também é notável pela sua versatilidade e pelo equilíbrio entre ataque e defesa. Cartas como *Mago Negro* e *Cavaleiro da Rainha Negra* são ícones no arsenal de Yugi, oferecendo tanto poder ofensivo quanto resistência nas batalhas. A inclusão de cartas como *Cilindro Mágico* e *Espadas da Luz Reveladora* permite que Yugi proteja seus pontos de vida enquanto prepara seus ataques devastadores.

Além das cartas poderosas, o deck de Yugi reflete sua personalidade e seu espírito de luta. Ele não apenas confia na força bruta, mas também na estratégia, no raciocínio rápido e na habilidade de se adaptar às situações em constante mudança. O duelo não é apenas uma questão de força, mas também de coração e inteligência, valores que Yugi incorpora a cada movimento.

Em resumo, o deck de Yugi no *Battle City* é um reflexo de sua jornada como duelista. Ele combina poder, estratégia e uma conexão profunda com as cartas, tornando-o um dos decks mais lendários da história de *Yu-Gi-Oh!*. Através desse deck, Yugi mostrou ao mundo o verdadeiro significado de ser um mestre duelista, conquistando a vitória com determinação e honra.
