**Yugi's Legendary Decks: Gadget**

 

O *Deck* de *Gadgets* do Yugi é um dos mais icônicos e estratégicos no universo de Yu-Gi-Oh!. Composto por cartas como *Green Gadget*, *Red Gadget*, e *Yellow Gadget*, este *deck* é reconhecido por sua capacidade de criar um fluxo constante de cartas para a mão do duelista, facilitando a invocação de poderosos monstros de Máquina e a realização de jogadas complexas.

 

O funcionamento central desse *deck* gira em torno das sinergias entre os *Gadgets*. Quando um Gadget é invocado, ele permite ao jogador adicionar outro Gadget de cor diferente à mão, garantindo que o duelista sempre tenha recursos disponíveis para manter a pressão sobre o adversário. Essa mecânica de busca constante faz com que o *deck* seja bastante consistente e versátil, oferecendo uma base sólida para diversas estratégias.

 

Além disso, o *deck* de Gadgets de Yugi se destaca pela facilidade com que pode invocar monstros *Xyz* e *Link*. Como os *Gadgets* são monstros de nível 4, eles podem rapidamente se reunir no campo para invocar poderosos monstros *Xyz*, como *Gear Gigant X*, ou monstros *Link*, como *Platinum Gadget*. Essas cartas permitem que o duelista mantenha o controle do campo e a vantagem nas jogadas, dificultando as respostas do oponente.

 

Outro ponto de destaque do *deck* é a sua compatibilidade com cartas de suporte como *Stronghold the Moving Fortress* e *Ultimate Offering*. *Stronghold* pode se transformar em um monstro poderoso quando três *Gadgets* estão no campo, enquanto *Ultimate Offering* permite invocações normais adicionais, acelerando ainda mais as estratégias do duelista.

 

Em suma, o *deck* de Gadgets de Yugi é um exemplo perfeito de como um conjunto de cartas aparentemente simples pode se tornar incrivelmente poderoso nas mãos de um duelista experiente. Sua consistência, capacidade de busca e sinergia tornam-no uma escolha formidável para quem deseja dominar o campo e manter o adversário sempre na defensiva.

Horus monsters can also go on the offense during the battlephase to help clear monsters before you start your Runick shenanigans, and they're quite difficult and annoying for your opponent to remove.

Out-resource your opponent with mass Horus summons and a bazillion draws!

GLHF Duelists!
Have fun:3

This is my irl Tearlaments Lightsworn and I love it, about the deck it's very solid, and have some solid end board if your luck doesn't betray you as
Tearlaments Kaleido-Hearth and Rulkallos, Grapha, Masquerade, Number 38, Minerva and other.

I like the infinite possibilities you can play those archetypes so you may add or remove things like the shaddoll or despia and add something like Punishment Dragon, endless variants.

So as for combo line, there is none because it all up to what you mill, fortunately there are many ways to mill from the lightsworn spells like solar recharge and charge of the light brigade, to both Minervas, Raiden, Foolish Burial for Tearlaments every mill 3 cards.

My gameplay:

Plan A: is to somehow get to two level 4 monsters with wiese or tearlaments even on the field make Minerva Syncro, Summon two lightsworns make the Minerva xyz, mill with the second effect of Syncro Minerva then mill with Minerva xyz and have in your GY despa, king of the swamp, shaddoll and most importantly tearlaments to fusion into something.
Plan B: instead of Minerva Synchro go to Visas Amritara search the fieldspell and do tearlaments fussions or go into Psy-Frame and with two level 8 into Number 32 Hope Harbinger.

In best case scenario you will have something between plan A and B and in worst your opponent will play Dimensional Shifter or Abyss Dweller or something to lock you.

I am open for suggestions and opinion on this decklist and strategy, I probably miss on something but you will figure it out. (Grapha is best for first fusion because of his effect overwriting)

deck_excerpt: Master I is no longer an illusion for these fusion beasts!
deck_description:
This season I decided to climb to Master I with Chimera, a deck which is a lot of fun to play both going 1st and 2nd. I started with a pure Chimera build (with just the Patchwork engine for the extra fusion power) while testing with the new Illusion cards, but ended switching it up to try the Yubel engine, which adds an additional monster negate to the end board in addition to extra fusion materials (this isn't an original idea, you can find other decks online using the Yubel engine like this)

The Chimera archetype is centered around the retrains of Chimera the Flying Mythical Beast and the newest addition to the Yu-Gi-Oh list of types, the Illusion monsters. The main gameplan of this deck is to summon Beast/Fiend/Illusion Fusion Monsters, while protecting your board and disrupting your opponent with the Illusion monster effects in the GY and Chimera Fusion plays, most notably summoning Guardian Chimera during your opponent's turn, gaining a lot of advantage that way. When going 2nd, you have the potential to OTK, by using some combination of big fusion monsters (either Guardian Chimera or Chimera the Illusion Beast), Nightmare Magician and/or Super Polymerization, but even if you don't OTK, you can setup a decent board after draining your opponent's resources.

The standard 1 card combo goes like this:

  • Summon Mirror Swordknight (which you can search with Cornfield Coatl), activate its effect, tributing itself to summon Big-Winged Berfomet from deck.
  • Use Big-Winged Berfomet to get Chimera Fusion and Gazelle the King of Mythical Claws to the hand.
  • Fusion Summon into Chimera the King of Phantom Beasts using the Berfomet and Gazelle. With Berfomet effect you can summon back Mirror Swordknight, and with Gazelle you can search some monster as follow-up (Cornfield Coatl or another Mirror Swordknight).
  • Activate Chimera Fusion effect in GY to get it back to hand, and set it.
  • During your opponent's turn, you can use Mirror Swordknight to summon another Big-Winged Berfomet if you need more follow-up (watch out for Called By or Ash Blossom though). You can also use Chimera Fusion whenever you want to summon a Guardian Chimera or any other Fusion monster that might be useful.

With this, you will rip 1 card from your opponent's hand, have a monster negate (Mirror Swordknight), a negate for effects that target your cards (Cornfield Coatl) and setup for a potential Guardian Chimera play with Chimera Fusion. Just don't forget that Swordknight and Coatl require you to control one of the Chimera fusions that are treated as "Chimera the Flying Mythical Beast" (Guardian Chimera doesn't count!)

With the Frightfur Patchwork and Gazelle the King of Mythical Claws (or Cornfield Coatl to search it), you can go for a different combo, usually more safe against handtraps:

  • Activate the Frightfur Patchwork to get Polymerization and Edge Imp Chain to the hand.
  • Use Polymerization to fuse into Chimera the King of Phantom Beasts using Edge Imp Chain and Gazelle the King of Mythical Claws.
  • With Gazelle the King of Mythical Claws effect, get Cornfield Coatl to search for Mirror Swordknight (or go directly for Swordknight instead if you already used Coatl to search Gazelle).
  • Summon Mirror Swordknight and do a combo similar to the 1 card combo previously explained, but summon the Berfomet the Mythical King of Phantom Beasts instead (possibly using Chimera the King of Phantom Beasts and Big-Winged Berfomet as materials). With its effect, you can either put another negate in the GY for future turns, or send Nightmare Magician to help OTK the next turn.

This combo ends on basically the same board as before, but you have more card advantage and follow-up, plus you setup your negates before the normal summon of Mirror Swordknight, meaning the rest of your combo is protected from most handtraps (no more Imperm on the Berfomet or Ash on the Swordknight).

If you open with Nightmare Throne (the Yubel engine), you can use it to destroy Spirit of Yubel from the deck and then use its effect to summon Yubel. From this point, you can go directly for Phantom of Yubel to protect the rest of your combos, or use Yubel as fusion material first if you don't feel threatened by handtraps. If you draw one of the garnets and no field spell, remember that Berfomet the Mythical King of Phantom Beasts can send a Yubel monster to the GY, since they are fiends, so you can also access Phantom of Yubel that way.

Regarding the remaining cards: Master Tao the Chanter is a good send off the Berfomet the Mythical King of Phantom Beasts effect, to summon back an Illusion from the GY. Nightmare Magician is not mandatory, but it's really fun to use and I like it a lot, plus it helps OTK, came up way more than I thought it would. Super Polymerization is a good board breaker, especially in conjuction with the Yubel monsters, but even standalone can break apart some boards, and I also like that it can be useful both going 1st and 2nd. The handtraps can be whatever you like, but one thing worth noting is that you draw cards during your opponent's turn with Guardian Chimera, so I actually prefer Effect Veiler over Infinite Impermanence in this deck.

The side decks include some cards I've tried or at least considered including, but didn't make the final cut: Emissary from the House of Wax is a cool defensive card, which you can search with Gazelle the King of Mythical Claws when you don't need anything else, even though it's a bit situational. King Tiger Wanghu can grant you a win against decks like Yubel, but otherwise does little. Diabolica the Draconique General could be useful to send off Berfomet the Mythical King of Phantom Beasts in grindy games, to get back Big-Winged Berfomet from the GY, since you turbo through your deck really quick (this archetype could really use some form of shuffling back your monsters into the deck), I didn't try it since I didn't want to add another garnet.

I hope you enjoy the deck, also check out the video to see the deck in action! I'm always open to feedback and ideas, so feel free to share those too!

deck_excerpt: "Oh, my opponent's playing the new XYZ support, this should be a fun and skill-based why are you searching Light Barrier?"
deck_description:
I've been having fun testing this deck out on sims. And by "fun", I mean "seeing my opponent quit when I summon The World gives me a feeling of satisfaction I haven't felt since building post-AGOV Nouvelles".

The deck plays pretty similarly to ABCXYZ builds, except with a bit of an extra step. If you can get a Union Hangar or Discolosseum on your field and Union Activation in your GY, you open up the gates to a full turnskip combo. All you have to do is get Torque Tune Gear on your field, tune it with either Union Controller or Fiendsmith Engraver to go into Ancient Fairy Dragon, which pops the field to add and activate Light Barrier. Then, when you summon XYZ-Hyper Dragon Cannon and ABC-Dragon Buster, immediately use Dragon Cannon's effect to summon Assault Core, Buster Drake, and Crush Wyvern back to the field. This triggers the Union Activation in your GY, allowing you to immediately add and then Normal Summon Arcana Force XXI - The World. Because you have Light Barrier, The World turnskips. If your opponent opens no or insufficient interaction, you are guaranteed to win as long as you don't mess up the combo.

The minimal Fiendsmith portion of the engine is just to feed materials on the field into the GY in order to trigger the non-once-per-turn effects of the ABC pieces. Running more Discolosseums than Reguluses is done in order to make it more likely to get a field spell on the field - if your opener doesn't include either of Union Hangar or Union Activation, opening Discolosseum at least ensures you have a Field Spell for Ancient Fairy Dragon. Mostly breakers in side for going second, the main-decked handtraps are run mostly for Crossout purposes. Obelisk is also for if you sided out the Arcana Force engine, as it's highly implied to be the recommended search for Union Activation in normal circumstances. Exciton Knight is a backup option if you get stopped at a critical point and can't set up anything.

The deck doesn't have the greatest consistency - you'll only pull this combo off about 60% of the time - it runs multiple bricks, including a total garnet in The World itself, falls apart to Shifter and Droll, and does have chokepoints around Union Controller and Platinum Gadget if you didn't hard open all of your starters and extenders.

But this deck is funny. And that is all that matters.

deck_excerpt: Pure Voiceless Voice (no Nadir Engine) for September 2nd Forbidden and Limited List.
deck_description: With the Limitation of Branded Fusion and Pot Of Prosperity, Voiceless Voice somehow has ended up as the biggest loser of the most recent Forbidden and limited list, with all the decks ahead of it getting hits that are either to generic tools or being limited enough to function with.  Branded Fusion takes away an engine that has contributed to consistency and a potential endboard piece, while the prosperity limit lowers the deck's ability to start with Lo, though 6 1 card combos is still plenty with all the 2-3 card combos the deck can get by on.  These hits open up more space for Hand Traps, with this list carrying 12 and 3 Kashtira Fenrir who, while not providing some of the setup value of BF, can still serve as a full tribute for 2 of 3 ritual outlets similar to Nibiru, while providing similar value to Mirrorjade in that its a point of interaction going first, and can help break boards going second by contesting established cards.  Selene and Accesscode give a line into big damage and board clearing.  Dharc and Lyna can help cheat materials getting into Selene and Accesscode while also fufilling the spellcaster requirement or, along with Closed Heaven, using Goddess to clear the opponent's board.  Silhouhatte Rabbit and Trick are a valuable backup line into an interuption if i get stopped, but have 2 bodies on field.  Otherwise this is fairly standard Voiceless Voice stuff.  S:P, Chaos Angel and TY-PHON are all being reprinted in the next few weeks in the Dueling Mirrors Tins, so those staples are about to get much more affordable.

Welcome to my Vampire build! 

-

If history serves, this deck was one of the first in my arsenal that had a crazy power ceiling compared to what I was using then. Especially in the Meta at the time. Think it was... whenever Halq was still legal. 

Needless to say, this deck could use some adjustments, though, I've found it to be very consistent if it's uncontested. 

- 

Vampires are a bit of a forgotten archetype in that they have an outdated gimmick. In (semi) recent years, it recieved some link and XYZ support in the form of [Vampire Sucker], [Vampire Fascinator] and [The Zombie Vampire]. 

Initially, in the older days of Boomer Monsters, Vampires were supposed to be a mill strategy, kind of like Runick, only worse. 
These new additions more focus on stealing monsters. As a Vampire would charm their victims, we're doing the same here along with a couple neat Spell cards that do just that. 

- 

Starting with key strategies: 

Believe it or not, the Extra Deck acts simply as an Extender pool and a last resort.

Your main focus Turn 1 or 2, is to get [Vampire Voivode] and [Doomking Balerdroch] on the field as soon as possible. 

Reason being, these two are your primary Negate bosses. Voivode in particular as their Negate IS NOT ONCE PER TURN but only affects anything activating in the Graveyard***. With Doomking in conjunction, also assuming you have [Zombie World] on the field, should protect Voivode from any unwanted attention. 

***Also, if there's a card with the same name on the field as one in the grave, you can Negate the Ignition of that one particular monster (as many times as you want :^) ) 

Getting to that point is a bit tricky, though. 

You will end up having to burn resources simply to survive, but most of the time, it's worth it. There isn't a ton of recursion for your Vampires, however, this is one of those decks where the ball is next to impossible to stop once its rolling. 

The Extra Deck, as I've mentioned, it more of a way to get you deeper into your Main Deck and other parts of the Extra. That said, the fun really starts once you start Link climbing. Sucker and Fascinator are absolutely crazy once you have [Zombie World] on the field. From Tributing your opponent's Monsters for a free Voivode to stealing one from the grave in order to get a quick Zombie Vampire, there are numerous lines of play that ensure the forbidability of this deck (despite how slow it is to actually get there in the first place.)

Lastly, I want to touch on [Vampire Fraulein]. This card, is THE saving grace of this deck. Not only do you have a free wall at the cost of your LP, but you can also Attack and potentially steal a monster. Absolute nonsense considering half the cards in this build do just that, but a free Level 5 body on top of an effect that IS NOT ONCE PER TURN :^)..... If you ask me, this with Uni-Zombie potentially getting Ash'd is a free Baronne. All I'm gonna say. 

Finally, the Sideboard includes more of the Handtraps we all know and love along with some additional options for extenders if this particular build doesn't tickle your fancy. 

[Lullaby of Obedience] 
probably being one of my favorite cards to tech in as it makes a great way to rip your opponent's Ash right out of the deck, if they have one.

- 

In conclusion, Vampires need work. However, Zombies are the one Type notorious for having insane amounts of support and next to hundreds of ways to really add some versatility to any deck. You're most likely bound to find several combinations that best suit your style of play. 

-

**Structure Deck: Ameaça dos Mortos-Vivos**

 

O "Structure Deck: Ameaça dos Mortos-Vivos" é um baralho temático do jogo de cartas Yu-Gi-Oh!, centrado em monstros do tipo Zumbi e na exploração de suas habilidades únicas. Este deck oferece uma combinação estratégica de cartas que permite ao jogador controlar e manipular o campo de batalha, utilizando as sinergias típicas dos monstros Zumbi, como reviver do cemitério e enfraquecer os monstros adversários.

 

Uma das principais características deste deck é a sua capacidade de transformar monstros do adversário em Zumbis, o que cria uma vantagem tática significativa. Ao fazer isso, o jogador pode utilizar efeitos que dependem do tipo Zumbi para neutralizar o campo inimigo e reverter situações desfavoráveis.

 

O deck também é conhecido por sua versatilidade e capacidade de adaptação. Com cartas que permitem a invocação especial de Zumbis do cemitério, ele oferece uma resiliência impressionante, tornando difícil para o oponente manter a vantagem por muito tempo. Além disso, com a habilidade de se beneficiar de cartas destruídas, o "Structure Deck: Ameaça dos Mortos-Vivos" recompensa um estilo de jogo agressivo, onde o sacrifício de recursos pode resultar em um retorno ainda maior.

 

Este baralho não é apenas poderoso, mas também é projetado para ser acessível a jogadores de todos os níveis de habilidade. Ele vem pré-construído, permitindo que novos jogadores experimentem a estratégia dos Zumbis sem a necessidade de investir em cartas adicionais imediatamente. Ao mesmo tempo, jogadores experientes podem facilmente incorporar cartas deste deck em suas estratégias mais amplas, personalizando e aprimorando seu poder de acordo com suas preferências individuais.

 

Em resumo, o "Structure Deck: Ameaça dos Mortos-Vivos" é uma adição formidável ao arsenal de qualquer duelista, oferecendo uma combinação única de poder, estratégia e acessibilidade, especialmente atraente para aqueles que apreciam o tema Zumbi e as dinâmicas de jogo que ele proporciona.

**Structure Deck: Scorching-Hot Earth (2005)**

 

Em 2005, a Konami lançou o *Structure Deck: Scorching-Hot Earth*, uma edição especial de deck para o jogo de cartas Yu-Gi-Oh!. Este deck foi projetado para os duelistas que apreciam estratégias agressivas e de alto impacto, com foco em monstros de atributo Fogo. 

 

O *Scorching-Hot Earth* trouxe uma seleção cuidadosamente escolhida de cartas, centradas em torno de monstros poderosos e efeitos devastadores que podem dizimar o campo do oponente rapidamente. A temática do fogo, que é a base deste deck, reflete-se em cartas como *Inferno Flame Emperor* e *Blazing Inpachi*, que não só possuem grande poder de ataque, mas também habilidades que podem transformar o campo de batalha em uma arena ardente. 

 

Além dos monstros, o deck incluía várias cartas mágicas e armadilhas que complementavam perfeitamente a estratégia do fogo, como *Molten Destruction*, que aumenta o poder dos monstros de atributo Fogo, e *Backfire*, que penaliza o oponente por destruir suas criaturas flamejantes.

 

O *Structure Deck: Scorching-Hot Earth* não apenas ofereceu aos jogadores uma maneira de entrar rapidamente no mundo de Yu-Gi-Oh! com uma estratégia competitiva pronta para uso, mas também se tornou uma peça de coleção valorizada entre os entusiastas do jogo. Este deck é um exemplo de como a Konami conseguiu capturar a essência de uma temática específica, fornecendo uma experiência de jogo intensa e imersiva para todos os duelistas.

deck_name: Structure Deck: The Sea Dragon God (2005)
deck_excerpt: Structure Deck: The Sea Dragon God (2005)
deck_description:
O *Structure Deck: The Sea Dragon God* foi lançado em 2005 como parte da série de *Structure Decks* do jogo de cartas Yu-Gi-Oh!. Esse baralho temático foi especialmente projetado para jogadores que gostam de utilizar monstros do tipo Água, oferecendo uma coleção pré-construída de cartas que facilitam a criação de estratégias em torno desse tipo específico de monstro.

 

O deck é centrado no poderoso monstro "Ocean Dragon Lord - Neo-Daedalus", uma carta icônica que não apenas lidera o baralho, mas também define sua estratégia principal. Neo-Daedalus é uma versão evoluída de "Levia-Dragon - Daedalus", um monstro clássico conhecido por sua habilidade devastadora de limpar o campo de cartas. Com Neo-Daedalus, os jogadores podem utilizar a habilidade de destruir todas as outras cartas no campo, exceto ele próprio, em troca de enviar a carta "Umi" do campo ao Cemitério. Essa habilidade de limpar o campo cria uma vantagem significativa, permitindo que os jogadores dominem o duelo com ataques poderosos.

 

Além do "Ocean Dragon Lord - Neo-Daedalus", o deck inclui outras cartas de suporte, como "A Legendary Ocean", que reduz o Nível dos monstros do tipo Água na mão e no campo em 1, facilitando a invocação de monstros mais poderosos. O deck também contém cartas de magia e armadilha que complementam a estratégia de controle do campo e amplificação de dano, como "Big Wave Small Wave" e "Tornado Wall".

 

O *Structure Deck: The Sea Dragon God* é especialmente apreciado por jogadores que preferem uma abordagem tática, focada em controle e destruição do campo adversário. A escolha cuidadosa de cartas dentro desse baralho oferece aos jogadores uma maneira eficaz de construir um deck competitivo em torno de monstros do tipo Água, equilibrando poder de ataque e habilidades defensivas.

 

Em resumo, o *Structure Deck: The Sea Dragon God* de 2005 se destacou como uma opção sólida para duelistas que desejam explorar as estratégias baseadas em monstros do tipo Água, combinando uma poderosa carta principal com suporte eficaz para garantir a vitória nos duelos.

deck_excerpt: I don't know if I'm cooking fine cuisine or filthy slop.
deck_description:
I absolutely love playing Purrely, and I've gone through two renditions of my Purrely deck to satisfy my playstyle. However, I am incredibly evil as well, and I've done dabbling in decks like Bystial-Runick. When I went to a local a few days back with my Spright Purrely deck, in an incredibly long game against a Feindsmith-White Forest player, a passer by commented on a potential stun Purrely variation with Runick as an engine. "That's disgusting" I thought, anything mixed with Runick is pure evil.

So when the August 31st Banlist was announced, I thought of creating a Purrely Runick deck utilizing some of the changes to the new F/L list. Some things of note...
 - Since no Runick hits were made, I decided to just utilize a complete package save for a few select cards (Smiting Storm is at 1 becasue it's decent in some situations, Dispelling is very situational, Golden Dropplet is a huge no).
 - 1 of each Fusion except Freki, Slepnir is diet S:P, Geri and Hugin for obtaining/looping Fountain, and Munin for time.
 - Eva's unbanning gives me an opportunity to test it in Purrely. It can search out a few options, specifically Purrely and any of the hand trap Heralds which are in this deck as well, as it can banish Hugin, Purrely, or Munin. Herald's not in this deck because Herald has no way of getting tributed.
 - 2 of Beauty and ExNoir, 1 of the rest of the Epurrelys. this is, for me, a standard of most Purrely decks.
 - This is a risky gambit, but 1 Stray Purely Street and 2 M.F. Purrelys. This is for consistency, as Runick makes it very easy to draw into Purrely.
 - Sylvan Princessprite at 1 is an optional no-brainer. Its effect to draw into a spell/trap is a near guaruntee.
 - Staples: S:P, Ash Blossom and Droll in Main/Extra, Harpie's and Ghost Bell/Ogre in the side. Numbers are at 2, but I'm keeping them at this for testing purposes.
 - Black Goat is a test, I see it in a few top decking Purrely builds, and this can be swapped out for anything.
 - Evenly Matched at 2 is something I'm mixed about, as it's only at 2 for fitting everything in the side deck.
 - Floodgates in side: 2 Graves, 1 Skill Drain, 1 Anti-Spell.
With Barded Fusion at 1 you need Crossout because you loose hard to hand traps and Bystials.
With Branded Fusion at 1, the deck looses harder to hand traps and Bystials, which is why you play Crossout.

One of the most important cards of his deck doesn't exist in Legacy of the Duelist Link Evolution, and this is the "Toon Bookmark".

deck_excerpt: A man's Snake-Eye will never die!!!!!!!!!
deck_description:
You average Snake-Eye deck for the most part, crucially, however, it's teched to bring out the maximum potential of Unstoppable Exodia.

On their own, both Millennium and Snake-Eye are very quick to start and end on their desired boards, but due to the nature of Ankh's effect, you cannot have an end board including Exodia as well as Snake-Eyes. To mitigate this, included in the list are 3 copies of G.B. Hunter, 3 copies of Spell Card "Monster Reborn" and 1 copy of ROTA. Both the main archetypes can combo off independant of each other, so the inclusion of these other cards are circumstantial in their importance and efficacy.

G.B. Hunter prevents any monster on the field from being shuffled back into the deck, and this conflicts with Millennium Ankh's effect to clear your board to bring out Exodia. If she's already on the field, you aren't even allowed to activate Ankh, but if she is summoned in chain after Ankh was already activated, that has a very different result. The ideal hand to pull off the G.B. shuffle skip is Ankh, Diabellstar, G.B., Spell Card "Monster Reborn", and Snake-Eye Ash.

Here's a demonstration of how this combo would play out:

  1. Activate Diabellstar from hand, sending G.B. Hunter from hand to graveyard, special summoning Diabellstar.
  2. Activate Diabellstar's on summon effect to add Sinful Spoils of Doom, Rciela to hand from deck.
  3. Normal summon Snake-Eye Ash, search Poplar, activate on summon effect to search desired Snake-Eyes Spell/Trap.
  4. Perform full Snake-Eye combo.
  5. Activate Millennium Ankh.
  6. Chain Link 2, activate Spell Card "Monster Reborn", special summoning G.B. Hunter from graveyard.
  7. Since Millennium Ankh was already activated, its effect must go through as much as possible. This means you reveal all 5 pieces of exodia from hand, field, or deck, special summon Unstoppable Exodia, then you would not shuffle all face-up non-Millennium and/or Exodia monsters from the field into the deck, instead leaving them untouched while sending Millennium Ankh to the graveyard, all due to G.B. Hunter's continuous effect.

This, of course, is inconsistent and quite a hopeful opening hand to expect for this combo, but it's not impossible. Due to the sheer consistency of both Millennium as well as Snake-Eye as engines, having an unideal hand for this best case scenerio is far from a devastating blow to the deck. There are more than enough stater options in this deck to mitigate any additional risk G.B. and Monster Reborn bring, and they are hardly bricks in hand either. Monster Reborn speaks for itself, while G.B. still has a useful blanket effect to engage in later turns against other decks that enjoy recycling their cards, as well as that she is pitch fodder for Diabellstar or even Ash and Oak if their summon effects are negated. She can also be placed in the back row by Wedju's effect to search any other MIllennium monster, then special summoned by Flamerge on your opponent's turn to interrupt a play.

Traptrix is a very interactive deck that can create some fun back and forth games which helped me get back into Yu-Gi-Oh.

The deck does struggle going second, but cards like Needle Ceiling and Destructive Daruma Karma Cannon along with the tool box in the extra deck help win games going second.

Needle Ceiling is really good due to the Traptrix extra deck monsters not being effected by trap cards. This does hurt when using Destructive Daruma Karma Cannon, but that card is so good I play it anyway.

Play this in the Edison Format. At the time of uploading, ygopro's deck builder did not allow Scrubbed Raid in the Edison Format.

This deck focuses on preventing your opponent's battle phase with a Scrubbed Raid + Black Ptera infinite loop and winning through alternate win conditions of Final Countdown or burning the opponent with Mass Driver. Black Ptera returns itself to the hand whenever it's sent from the field to the graveyard, except by being destroyed in battle, so it makes great fodder for cards like Mass Driver, Scrubbed Raid, and Torrential Tribute. Also supporting this strategy are the Imperial Custom + Metal Reflect Slime combo and the Quillbolt Loop. Imperial Custom protects Metal Reflect Slime from all forms of destruction, including battle, making it the ultimate wall. The Quillbolt Loop uses Imperial Iron Wall, Quillbolt Hedgehog, and a tuner monster like Plaguespreader Zombie to provide infinite fodder for Mass Driver. You can special summon Quillbolt Hedgehog from your graveyard with its own effect while you control a tuner monster, but it's normally banished when it leaves the field. Imperial Iron Wall prevents Quillbolt Hedgehog from being banished, so you can create an infinite loop by tributing it with Mass Driver, then special summoning it back from the graveyard.

deck_excerpt: Blue-eyes, Buster Blader, Spirit with eyes of blue, Enhanced metalmorph
deck_description:
This deck is insane. From blue-eyes endboards with magia to the buster lock, it has it all.

The new blue-eyes support makes it so that buster whelp is easily searchable, so you can cut a lot of BB cards/bricks. 

If you happen to draw the bricks (buster blader or memories), you can just shuffle it back with illusion of chaos so that prologue is live again. 

If not, you can still makes the BB lock with protector whelp and all the lvl 1 tuners in the deck.

Where arf thou is such a good card, it can search all lvl's 1's (whelp, sage, maiden, copycat, magicians soul, veiler, droll).

Making magia is easy as magicians soul can dump illusion of chaos which can be used to fuse into magia. 

Magicians soul can also discard true light to draw, because maiden can set it from the from the grave aswell. 

Making red-eyes black full metal dragon is very easy with all the high lvl dragons this deck can summon. 

The reason for 45 cards instead of 40 is to lower the chances of drawing your bricks, the deck is consistent enough where this doesn't hurt a lot.

There are a lot of cards you can side out to add more going second cards if you wish to do so.
Have fun ^^

Post Banlist Deck Profile for Voiceless Voice

**Structure Deck: Warrior's Triumph (2005)**

 

O **Structure Deck: Warrior's Triumph**, lançado em 2005, é uma coleção especial de cartas do popular jogo de cartas colecionáveis Yu-Gi-Oh!. Este deck pré-construído foi projetado para jogadores que preferem usar monstros do tipo Guerreiro, que são conhecidos por sua versatilidade e força em combate. O deck foi meticulosamente montado para oferecer uma combinação equilibrada de monstros, magias e armadilhas, permitindo aos duelistas desenvolverem estratégias eficazes no campo de batalha.

 

A peça central deste deck é a carta "Gilford the Legend", um monstro Guerreiro de nível 8 com um efeito poderoso que permite equipar a si mesmo com várias cartas de Equipamento do cemitério, aumentando significativamente seu poder. Além disso, o deck inclui uma variedade de monstros guerreiros de diferentes níveis, como "Command Knight" e "Marauding Captain", que complementam as habilidades de "Gilford the Legend" e ajudam a criar um campo de batalha quase impenetrável.

 

Além dos monstros, o **Structure Deck: Warrior's Triumph** contém uma seleção de cartas mágicas e de armadilhas que reforçam a temática guerreira. Cartas como "Reinforcement of the Army" e "The A. Forces" ajudam a fortalecer o exército do duelista, enquanto armadilhas como "Sakuretsu Armor" oferecem proteção contra ataques inimigos. Essa combinação de cartas não só aumenta o poder ofensivo dos monstros, mas também protege o duelista contra possíveis ameaças.

 

O deck foi especialmente projetado para ser uma excelente escolha tanto para novos jogadores quanto para veteranos que desejam aprimorar suas estratégias com monstros do tipo Guerreiro. Sua estrutura equilibrada permite que os jogadores se adaptem a diferentes situações durante o duelo, proporcionando uma experiência de jogo dinâmica e emocionante.

deck_excerpt: The final version of a fun crystal beast deck

deck_description:
O *Structure Deck - Magician's Judgment*, lançado em 2005, é uma coleção icônica de cartas para o jogo de cartas colecionáveis Yu-Gi-Oh!. Esse baralho tem como tema principal a magia e é centrado em torno dos famosos monstros do tipo Spellcaster, como o lendário *Dark Magician*, um dos personagens mais conhecidos e reverenciados no universo de Yu-Gi-Oh!.

 

O deck foi projetado para jogadores que desejam construir uma estratégia baseada em monstros e magias poderosas. Ele oferece uma combinação equilibrada de cartas que suportam a invocação rápida de monstros do tipo Spellcaster, ao mesmo tempo que protege o jogador contra ataques adversários. Entre as cartas notáveis do baralho, destacam-se aquelas que fortalecem a defesa e o ataque do *Dark Magician*, permitindo ao jogador dominar o campo de batalha.

 

Além de focar em monstros poderosos, o *Structure Deck - Magician's Judgment* inclui várias cartas de armadilha e de magia que complementam a estratégia principal do deck. Essas cartas auxiliam na destruição de monstros adversários e na manutenção do controle do duelo, proporcionando ao jogador uma vantagem significativa ao longo do jogo.

 

O lançamento do *Magician's Judgment* em 2005 foi bem recebido pelos fãs da franquia, especialmente aqueles que já tinham uma afinidade com o *Dark Magician*. Este deck não só trouxe novas cartas e estratégias para o jogo, mas também reforçou a popularidade do arquétipo Spellcaster, que continua a ser um dos mais amados pelos duelistas.

 

Em suma, o *Structure Deck - Magician's Judgment* é uma peça essencial na coleção de qualquer fã de Yu-Gi-Oh!. Ele oferece uma excelente base para jogadores que desejam explorar e dominar o poder dos monstros do tipo Spellcaster, ao mesmo tempo em que proporciona uma experiência de jogo desafiadora e recompensadora.

**Título: Structure Deck: Guardian's Fortress (2005)**

 

Lançado em 2005, "Structure Deck: Guardian's Fortress" é um dos produtos mais icônicos da história dos jogos de cartas Yu-Gi-Oh. . Com uma temática focada na defesa e no poder dos heróis e monstros divinos, este deck foi pensado para jogadores que buscam uma estratégia forte e não conseguem resistir aos ataques devastadores de seus oponentes.

 

A estrela principal deste deck de criação é "Exodus, Guard Master", um monstro de efeito terra que representa o núcleo defensivo da estratégia. Sempre que um monstro do tipo pedra é invocado, sua habilidade especial é ativada, causando dano ao inimigo e sua defesa é extremamente alta. Além disso, o deck contém monstros do tipo pedra e outras cartas que reforçam o conceito de proteção e prevenção, como as cartas ‘Esfinge Guardiã’ e ‘Hierakosphynx’.

 

Além de monstros, o baralho contém uma variedade de cartas de feitiços e armadilhas para complementar sua estratégia defensiva. Cartas como ‘Shield and Sword’, que alteram o ataque e a defesa de todos os monstros do campo, e ‘Traveler’s Trial’, uma armadilha que bloqueia o ataque do oponente, mostram claramente como este deck visa alterar a defesa. Torna-se uma arma mortal. Esta carta permite aos jogadores manter o controle do campo usando a defesa do monstro para virar o jogo contra eles.

 

"Rescue Deck: Guardian's Fortress" é um favorito entre jogadores que preferem uma estratégia lenta e cuidadosa. Ao contrário dos decks que focam em ataques rápidos e poderosos, este deck força os jogadores a construir defesas sólidas enquanto esperam o momento certo para atacar. Isso é ótimo para jogadores experientes e para aqueles que estão aprendendo a importância de uma boa defesa no jogo.

 

Além do valor estratégico, este baralho também é nostálgico. Para muitos atletas, é um símbolo de uma época em que paciência e perseverança eram iguais a dificuldades. Até hoje, “Rescue Deck: Guardian’s Fortress” ainda é lembrado por aqueles que o usaram para criar novas e surpreendentes estratégias no campo de batalha.

 

Resumindo, o “Structure Deck: Guardian’s Fortress” de 2005 não apenas introduziu uma nova maneira de jogar Yu-Gi-Oh!, mas também inaugurou uma era em que o jogo se concentrava na defesa e no ataque. A combinação de monstros poderosos e estratégias de defesa únicas tornou-se um marco na história dos jogos e permanece relevante e duradoura até hoje...

deck_excerpt: Structure Deck: Ruler of the Gale (2006)
deck_description:
Lançado em 2006, “Structure Deck: Ruler of the Gale” é o popular Yu-Gi-Oh! É uma das muitas edições especiais da franquia. Cada deck da série "Rescue Deck" é cuidadosamente projetado para fornecer aos competidores uma estratégia específica e coesa, facilitando a construção de decks competitivos do zero.

 

No caso de "Master of the Windfury", o foco muda para monstros com efeito de vento. O efeito do vento é famoso pela sua agilidade e efeitos que dificultam a vida dos adversários. O baralho contém combinações de cartas que permitem aos jogadores controlar o campo, lançar ataques rápidos e utilizar os efeitos dos monstros que retornam à sua mão ou ao campo, promovendo a natureza fluida e dinâmica do jogo.

 

Uma das grandes vantagens deste baralho é que as cartas não apenas complementam a estratégia geral, mas também reforçam o enredo ao apoiar monstros aéreos. A seleção de feitiços e armadilhas em “Ruler of the Gale” foi cuidadosamente escolhida para aumentar o poder dos monstros e permitir que os competidores enfrentem diferentes desafios em diferentes níveis.

 

"Deck Building: Master of Windfury" não é apenas uma excelente base para construir decks mais fortes, mas também um excelente recurso introdutório para quem deseja explorar estratégias baseadas no elemento Vento. Seja para competição ou uso geral, este deck representa uma combinação equilibrada de potência, velocidade e versatilidade, tornando-o a escolha perfeita para muitos Yu-Gi-Oh! Será uma escolha popular entre os jogadores. Desde o seu lançamento em 2006..

deck_description:
**Design Deck: Pulse of the Dinosaur**, lançado em 2006, é um dos designs de deck do Yu-Gi-Oh! que traz ao jogo um tema especial focado em dinossauros. Este deck foi especialmente desenvolvido para jogadores que desejam explorar e apreciar o poder dos dinossauros gigantes, conhecidos por seu alto poder de ataque e poder destrutivo.

 

Pulse of the Dinosaur destaca-se por oferecer uma série de monstros dinossauros, feitiços e armadilhas que complementam este tema e criam uma sinergia que permite aos jogadores executar uma estratégia sólida. Os destaques deste pacote incluem monstros como “Super Conductor Tyranno”, que pode causar danos significativos aos oponentes, e “Black Tyranno”, que tem a capacidade de atacar diretamente se certas condições forem atendidas. Além disso, o baralho inclui cartas de feitiços e armadilhas que não apenas protegem seus dinossauros, mas também podem remover as defesas do seu oponente, deixando-os vulneráveis ​​aos seus monstros.

 

O lançamento de Pulse of the Dinosaur foi significativo porque popularizou o uso de dinossauros em jogos competitivos, forneceu um ponto de entrada para novos jogadores e também forneceu uma ferramenta útil para jogadores experientes que buscavam mudar sua estratégia. É lembrado como um deck que, apesar de seu design simples, proporcionou uma base sólida para jogadores que desejavam explorar o poder e a ferocidade dos dinossauros em Yu-Gi-Oh!..

deck_name: Elemental Hero - Based off Master Duel Event
deck_description: Copied from an event we had on master duel once

Hello guys this is my dreammirror fiendsmith deck!

My first deck profile here, but ill try to explain it as good as I can.

Dreammirror is my favorite deck for a long time, but since they never got more support the deck couldnt compete even with the rogue decks anymore, but with fiendsmith the deck got alot more consistent, can play sometimes through handtraps and even if the dreammirror line gets stopped, u can still accomplish something on the field, as before u were doomed to one ash blossom( sometimes u still will be)

I tested out alot, different variants from this, but lets start why i include the 5 card yubel package here

Phantom of yubel can help u go full combo without worry about a monster handtrap going first, or can bait the enemy ash with the fieldspell.

I rly like it, but we needed to add 2 more bricks into the deck, thats why i had the best results with a deck that is a little over 40 cards. I play less of 3 ofs to minimize drawing dead cards going second so we have a good chance of winning. Theres still alot that can be changed, but in my opinion the decks core with fiendsmith and dreammirror is around 25-30 cards if u wanna play the yubel package aswell, i rly like it alot. Sometimes i side it out for more going second cards like evenly against decks with strong endboards on field.

So what has now changed for dreammirror?

With dreammirror u can go into the fiendamizh engine with one card, neiroy the lvl3 fiend, since he can change from dark to light fiend if his effect resolves, so u can bridge into the fiendsmith link 1 and go throm there. The combo usualy looks like this, so that u use the link 2 to fusionsummon by shuffling back from grave ur ikelos and neiroy, to get our dreammirror tormentor for a omni negate. Consistent without having to search for the fusion spell. Before it was that if u didnt draw ur trap, the black knight or the fusion spell, u had only one search so u had to decide which of the 3 u will get. Now u have always the fusion with 1 card, so if u drew for example one of the knights, u can search for the trap since its the only piece missing for ur ,,best,, endboard option. And the other way around if u drew the trap, u can get the knights or the trap. If u go first, u can also always search with ikelos one of the traps, and use maras effect to tribute herself and special ikelos from the deck in the enemies turn, so u can get ur black knight out from hand also in his turn. Also u can run now less copies of the dreammirror monster, since now u can shuffle them back into the deck, so fiendamith also helps with ur grind game and recycling ur disruptions. U could play one less of the light lvl 3, but if u draw it u need to change ur combo line a bit to the worse, thats why i decided to play 2.

Overall i love to play this variant, i think that something into this direction is probably the most viable way now to play dreammirror, and also depending on hand u can also get tormentor+ desirae in the same turn out, that provides u also with another 2 disruptions.

The perfect hand can accomplish actually a decent amount of disruptions, with yubel + tormentor,+ desirae+ black knight+ 1 of the traps+ effect fromthe oneiros when one monster u control tributes itself for another pop,+ if desirae leaves the field another disruption. If they play into everything thats 7 disruptions, but its rarely gonna happen.

If u have thoughts or questions i would like to hear them :)

Atualmente temos um formato de jogo bem caracterizado por vários efeitos de monstros e cards de armadilha/magia que buscam outros monstros, invocam por special summon.

Esse deck trabalha principalmente pelo mecanismo de negação, onde temos várias traps normais para que possa ativar o efeito cascata do combo principal da Traptrix Sera, de realizar uma special summon do deck. É um modelo balanceado, com foco nos primeiros turnos de frear o oponente, para poder encaixar o combo no timing certo. 

Caso seja necessário fugir dos monstros traptrix, temos os XYZ genéricos para segurar o combo do oponente, como o Bagooska, Time Thief e os Stellarknight.

O modelo tem funcionado muito bem para mim, e acredito ser uma das melhores versões que seja possível jogar nos torneios locais contra o meta atual.

deck_excerpt: Limits on Prosperity and Sangen Summoning? It is Blaster's time to shine in Tenpai!
deck_description:
The September 2024 Banlist took away 4 integral starters to Tenpai Dragon, somewhat hampering the consistency and resilience of the deck. We lost 2 Pot of Prosperity and 2 Sangen Summoning! Okay, we expected the deck to be hit in this fashion since they are low rarity and cheap anyways - Konami loves to destroy budget decks. We got away with only a slap on the wrist this banlist, so the Tenpai strategy is very playable!

Losing 2 POT OF PROSPERITY kind of hurts because it is often used to dig for that ideal boardbreaker to split open our opponent's board. It can also be used to dig for a starter, since Tenpai can still reliably OTK despite Prosperity's "half-damage" clause. 
 
Losing 2 SANGEN SUMMONING is very painful because it's such a cracked card for the strategy. Sangen summoning renders our Fire Dragons basically invincible during Main Phase 1, so we can start nuke apart our opponent's board with Black Rose Dragon, or combo unimpeded straight into Transcendant Dragion to prevent our opponent's activations during the Battle Phase. Instead we only have 1 copy now, which makes Tenpai plays more vulnerable since we'll run into Sangen Summoning less often. It's also a searcher for Tenpai monsters! 
 
I replaced the 4 lost cards in my decklist with:
 
1 copy of BLASTER, DRAGON RULER OF INFERNOS with 1 GOLD SARCOPHAGUS. Blaster is a very good utility card in Tenpai - it can search for any Fire Dragon once banished with Gold Sarcophagus! It is also a boardbreaker since it can discard itself and 1 other card to destroy a card on your opponent's field, such as a pesky floodgate or monster preventing your OTK. 
 
I added 1 more copy of TENPAI GENROKU, bringing the number up from 1 to 2. Now when you hard draw it, you won't feel as bad since you have another in your deck! It's the deck's "Poplar" being able to summon once added to hand, so it's crucial that this semi-garnet/starter stays in your deck so you can search it with Bystial Magnumhut, Sangen Summoning and Sangen Kaimen. 
 
For the last card, you can add anything else you want. I personally used only 2 Pot of Prosperity in my decklist, so I only lost 3 cards from the banlist rather than 4.
 
If you're like me who refuses to buy into approx. $100USD per copy Fiendsmith Engravers, I HIGHLY recommend Tenpai this format! Snake-Eye Fiendsmith and Yubel Fiendsmith got somewhat weaker, especially losing Apollousa in their endboards, so boards are much easier to crack open nowadays. 
 
Tenpai is only going to get stronger with the release of Rage of the Abyss in October as well, because Mulcharmy Fuwaross will grant this blind second strategy so much gas and turn-stopping power that you'll OTK most opponents when you resolve the card!
 
Despite the limit of both Sangen Summoning and Pot of Prosperity, Tenpai Dragon still functions the same way post September banlist, albeit less consistently and reliably. 

If you want a detailed guide and combo on how to use the deck, check out my earlier article by clicking here. 

GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: Bystial + Maliss? How deep does this rabbit hole go?

Extenders

The Maliss archetype has some synergies with Bystials because they're dark monsters that can special summon themselves if they're banished. Chaos Space can start your Bystial plays by sending a light or dark monster from your hand to the graveyard to search for The Bystial Lubellion.

Catche Eve L2 is a light cyberse that can special summon herself from your hand by reducing the level of a level 3 or higher monster you control by exactly 2.

Haggard Lizardose is a link monster with an unrestricted effect that can banish a Maliss monster from your graveyard.

deck_name: Mai Valentine - Harpie Lady / Pet Dragon (LOTD:LE)
deck_description:
This is a deck for Mai Valentine, one of the first female characters in Yugioh Original which were able to compete at such a high level.

Mai's deck theme is based on the Harpie archetype. But this archetype comes with so many problems... A lot of the cards search certain names. So, you have to understand and learn every single card's NAME and RULLING such as: "harpie" cards, "harpie lady" monsters, cards that mentions "harpie lady sisters"

While this seems like not a big deal in the first glance, after some hours of trying and testing you can understand that there are so many limitations and bad cards. One even bigger problem is that the extra deck cards like "Harpie's Pet Phantasmal Dragon" and "Harpie Conductor" are very specific of what their effects can do and there is no real reason to summon them. To make these cards work, you can build the deck around heavy-stun with cards as "Gravity Bind" and "Level Limit - Area B", but it will make the gameplay very slow and versus strong decks like Odion's or Vetrix you might lose in one turn.

On the other hand this strategy is quite OK, as you mostly use rank 4 or 7 monsters and many Link monsters, so YOU will be able to attack your opponent. If you don't need one of these floodgates to your field, you can always destroy them with "Harpie's Hunting Ground". One more thing that I don't like and it's so difficult to execute is the combo with "Harpie Harpist" + "Harpie Dancer" + "Harpie Conductor". If you are fine with these mechanics this control deck can be useful to you with the addition of "Ancient Pixie Dragon".

For me this final deck that I've came up with is quite less complex and easy to use (Worth mentioning the strongest card out there "Lightning Chidori"). The most reliable combo is the one with "Harpie Channeler", you can go for a Rank 7 xyz monster or for "Harpie Perfumer" to get access to one of your spell cards. Cards like "Aqua Chorus" and "Phalanx Pike" are very strong with this archetype and they can give you a very big advantage (in one game my 1400 attack Harpie went to 9400 attack with Phalanx Pike). My decision of running 2 "Blazing Mirror Force" instead of "Mirror Force" is that a single combo of Harpies can deal around 4000 dmg or more, so you might OTK after it's activation in your turn.

Harpies act like cheap bodies without huge attack points, that's why I also run 3 copies of "Harpie Lady 1" to boost the other cards a bit, while I use and some synchro monsters to be able to have a second plan of beatsticks for over 3000 attack points. You might have big trouble in the first matches, but as you continue playing this deck you will understand that you don't have to overuse these cheap bodies for extra deck's monsters. It's better to have patient and wait of your opponent's big threats before you act.

deck_description:
My take on the new Mermail and Atlantean support featuring an Ice Barrier engine. I personally like the Ice Barrier cards for a going 1st strategy and being able to side them out when going second without taking out your main engine and handtraps. You can cut this deck down to 40 cards by going with 2 copies of the Mermail Shadow Bodyguards. There are other options for the Mermail Atlantean deck instead of the Ice Barrier engine like running the Levirtue Dragon package for an Icarus Attack setup.

There are some other options you can run in the side deck for sure. Crossout Designator comes to mind with Mulcharmy Fuwaross being a powerful handtrap that will be arriving in the upcoming Rage of the Abyss set.

deck_name: Six Samurai post ROTA theory craft
deck_excerpt: Theory crafting Six samurai to be rogue competitively.
deck_description:
Looking for suggestions for the deck to make it more competitively viable. While this version does not run either of the mulcharmy’s, there is flexibility to change out cards. After reviewing and testing, I find there are some key takeaways with the new cards coming.

  • There should be no tuners besides the new ones.
    • All of the other tuners from the Shien/Six Samurai archetypes have had the issue where they need to be summoned through the use of something else going right to work. I.E. Kageki, Asceticism, Dojo, etc. These all hinge on the condition these effects resolve without interruption. This has been fixed with both of the new tuners only requiring 1 other six samurai monster. Even if the monster is negated, which at times can be bated with Kageki, you still have the monster on board making your lvl 5/6 synchros still very accessible. As a bonus, even if you don’t synchro with them, you are able to search for one of the followup spells or extenders when sent to the GY.
    • I do believe there can be a case made for Shien’s Squire as it is a lvl 1 tuner that can be revived through gateway, but does cost you a few things.
      • If you ever draw it, it is a garnet and should immediately be used as fodder for battle shogun.
      • It requires a significant amount of resources to use, which could be used for more synchro plays which can be significantly stronger.
      • With it coming at the cost of a garnet, it is also really only useful for the Naturia Synchros, specifically Beast. It is significantly easier to make Shi En since you have a lot of ways to manipulate who is on board, when, and at what level.
  • There are no 1 card starters, but there are several 1.5 card starts.
    • With the introduction of the tuners and the new six strike card, there are several ways to start with just any 2 different named six samurai monsters.There are some setups that are terrible, but they can work.
    • This limitation prevents the deck from ever being a tier 1 strategy in today’s metagame, but that is fine for a local or even regional level strategy.
    • Because of this limitation you are susceptible to being hand trapped. My build attempts to limit how impactful 1-2 hand traps are to the overall strategy, which I will review further.
  • There are tech choices that can be made for the deck that limits the impact of hand traps to a degree.
    • One of the first choices that many I have seen go to is Fire Flint lady which prevents targeting 1 warrior monster it summons from the hand. This is good in theory, but has some of the same issues I have mentioned above.
      • It can be a garnet if you don’t have the right setup for it, namely Kizaru or Hatsume.
      • This increases the volatility of your hand since you are using 1 card to protect a 2nd very specific card. You now effectively are looking at a 2.5-3 card start which is not viable in a realistic setting, of which, you are only running 1 FFL at most.
      • Since this is a lvl 1 monster, and is only searchable with ROTA, you either add in “durendal” or use rota to search. And in a 40 card deck, you are rarely seeing this if ever.
    • With the new tuners, namely anarchist, we are able to add a card that I have never seen used, even in the early days when it was the original 6. Cunning of the Six Samurai. With Cunning of the Six Samurai we are able to do several things to help elevate the deck.
      • With Cunning being a searchable card, we can use at 1 to protect, extend, and reset interactions. This is not as impactful on its own which is why I run just 1 compared to 3 Asceticism. Asceticism turns any of our weaker monsters, 500 atk. or less, into either a Klesha or a link play. Whereas Cunning is after our initial setup is completed.
      • A standard setup will have us go into Klesha before or at 5th summon, protecting from Nibiru as well as all handtraps EXCEPT, Imperm and the new dominus trap cards. Cunning allows us to dodge Imperm as the only remaining hand trap that 99% of players would have to stop us that Klesha would not be able to stop. If they have either Dominus card, they are just a better gamer.
      • If we did not have to use Cunning, we can use it for either of the following.
        • If we used a Synchro Six Samurai to link play, we can use a Kizan to revive the monster.
        • Reset an interaction of either Shi En synchro to negate a s/t or monster negation on either our turn or our opponents.
        • Extend to make a better end board.
    • For other tech choices, it would most likely be in the extra deck and how you build it.
      • If you want to build with the Naturia monsters, you can/must run the Shien’s Squire. In addition to that, it wouldn’t be terrible either to run Proxy F Magician and Naturia Exterio since you would be able to make it fairly easily with all the material you would have. If you do this, you would need to make significantly more counters or remove other cards such as some link or XYZ I have in my build for example.
      • You could run a more XYZ heavy build and go into Utopic Future/Utopic Draco Future for another monster to negate and gain control of your opp monster.
      • In the main deck, for generating counters, you could run 2 Shinai and 2 Mizuho. With this, you will need to have at least 1 Saryuja in extra or use one of your extending spells to summon the first out. This will increase deck size and potentially reduce consistency. But that is a trade off for a better end board. Reminder though, you will need to generate at least 2n+1 counters where n is the summons, otherwise there is no purpose for this loop.
  • The flexibility I feel truly lies in the non-engine, which for me is about ~10 in the main deck give or take based on the ratios. As well as the extra and side deck. All of which can be determined by the individual. My philosophy when building this was I will go first and blow them out with a large setup. And if I go 2nd I will rip apart their setup and then build mine up. I use the hand traps I do as they are the most effective and efficient to all decks in the game.

I do think the deck has potential, but in the current state of the game, there are simply better decks, but this is a favorite and I believe it has at least tier 2 potential. There are a few different builds for the deck, this is just the one I have landed on currently, but am not wholly decided on this as the end. I do not like this being reduced to an FTK deck with cannon soldier/amazoness archer or the like, so please no. I am not THAT degenerate.

Let me know what your thoughts are, and any suggestions. I did put my opinions on certain choices of why I do not do them, but would still like to hear the opinions of others and if there are other schools of thought on them. I have been playing the deck off and on since Storm of Ragnarok was released back in 2011.

deck_excerpt: Freeze your foes with floodgates to Masters 1 with Ice Barrier!
deck_description:
The full power of the Ice Barrier Dragons have been unsealed with Wings of the Guardian, transforming this previously underpowered fan favourite archetype to a proper rogue contender!
 
Ice Barrier now has a proper gameplan and win condition, opting to turbo out their ace boss monster Lancea, Ancestral Dragon of the Ice Mountain so that it can summon an Ice Barrier army as your opponent continues to special summon! Soon, your opponent's strategy will freeze in it's tracks as you summon Ice Barrier floodgates like General Raiho (functions like Skill Drain) and Medium (functions like Anti-Spell) with Lancea. This "synchro boss monster turbo" win con makes Ice Barriers very straighforward and simple to play - almost reminiscent of Swordsoul.

The new support combined with the recent Ice Barrier structure deck support makes Ice Barrier very consistent, featuring many 1-2 card combos complete with starters (Revealer, Hexa Spirit, Medallion) and extenders (Georgius, Speaker, Freezing Chains). This enables the deck to field alot of staple cards, allowing the strategy to effectively compete with other powered combo decks with it's many handtraps and boardbreakers.

The Extra Deck is also mostly a synchro toolbox this deck can access full of offensive (Chengying) and defensive (Toad, Aegirine) boss monsters to best tackle the gamestate.

If you want a full combo guide on this deck, check out Team Solemn Circus' video here.

If you want a similar guide + combo article on Ice Barrier Runick (arguably stronger than the "pure" version), click here.
 
GLHF Duelists!

Simply put, I love this deck. The card art is amazing and the play-style is really fun. The only this I hate about it is the price of the cards (like seriously man, Jesus Christ 160$ for Starfrost) but I think if you want to play this deck irl, I suggest buying this deck in singles by buying like PSA 7s bc that's when the price really goes down. 

This deck has A LOT of flexibility. You can play a more Scareclaw version, a more Tearlaments version, or a more Kashtira version. This one is my personal favorite (NOT the strongest one). I prefer my decks being fun to play, not meta broken, so I'm keeping this version, BUT, with that being said I CAN, see this deck going to tier 1 or even tier 0 with some careful planning alongside Kashtira (but I don't recommend it).

Anyway, have fun, I hope you like this deck as much as I do

deck_excerpt: Kuribohs, but they're just an engine
deck_description:
You know, for being the Kuriboh obsessed freak that I am, I never really post any of my decks involving Kuriboh at all, so let's fix that~!

Kuriboh Horus is a deck I came up with somewhere in the middle of August that just kinda sounded like it worked perfectly well together. This is a deck that seeks to abuse the capability of the Horus monsters to make Rank 8 or Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess negates going first and their easy access to special summoning themselves from the grave to make easy link 4s or Underworld Goddess to start breaking boards when going second. Since the main engine is so small here(Kuribohs take up 11 spots while Horus takes up 9 to total half a deck), the deck is allowed to run a lot of non-engine and going 2nd board breaks involving the capability to main deck The Winged Dragon of Ra - Sphere Mode at 2 copies on top of the mandatory 3 Maxx "C", 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, 2 Called by the Grave and 1 Crossout Designator. The general gameplan of this deck is to use the Horus engine and Kuriboh with Multiply combo to facilitate recursion and strong negate and disruption based boards while sitting on different types of towers created through I:P Masquerena.

To explain Kuribohs, the main Kuriboh engine we're running here is the Multiply Engine with one single Kuribohrn to allow for recursion to protect ourselves and create follow-up plays if the opponent can break through a going first board where you can get Kuribohrn into the GY. Since we're doing the Multiply Engine, we want to run 3 copies of Kuriboh, 3 copies of The Flute of Summoning Kuriboh, 1 copy of One for One and 3 copies of Multiply. The full playsets of each gives us more opportunity to draw into Multiply itself with more opportunities to make it live through the different ways of forcing Kuriboh onto the board to make a board full of  5 Kuriboh Tokens to do large link plays. Getting a full Multiply board off in a game without getting interrupted when going 2nd will result in always being able to make either a 3 material Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess, Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax or Underworld Goddess of the Closed World with the I:P Masquerena protection on them, making a fat towers for you to sit on potentially without requiring your normal summon.

As for Horus, we run the 3 King's Sarcophagus with 3 Imsety, Glory of Horus to have the most access to our Horus engine, and one of each other Horus Monster that isn't Dark Flame Deity: Hapi, Guidance of Horus, Duamutef, Blessing of Horus and Qebehsenuef, Protection of Horus. The extra Horus monsters past Hapi is to either have more access to 2 different Rank 8 Disruptions where you feel it's needed most. Generally on blind going first you'll probably make Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy and Number 90: Galaxy-Eyes Photon Lord. Occassionally you'll want to make The Zombie Vampire to hopefully be able to extend plays further in an attempt to mill more Horus monsters or a Kuribohrn for a follow-up recursion while also stealing monsters for a potential further link out. If you're able to go second and make a rank 8 knowing you'll be able to shut-down GY plays, Number 68: Sanaphond the Sky Prison is there for you since this deck lacks access to Abyss Dweller.

Afterwords we have Keldo the Sacred Protector and Mudora the Sword Oracle for pitch material for Imsety of King's Sarcophagus to get access to Horus and have quick play GY disruption, 2 copies of The Winged Dragon of Ra - Sphere Mode for board breaking to remove problematic monsters that can't be removed by effects, 1 copy of Nibiru, the Primal Being as a target for Crossout Designator since Multiply will always set-up an opponent's Nibiru, but also it comes in handy as its own going second option if you open it, 2 Evenly Matched to break boards and 3 Infinite Impermanence for going first or going second disruption.

For the extra deck, we already went over the Rank 8s in depth but to recap we have Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy, Number 68: Sanaphond the Sky Prison, Number 90: Galaxy-Eyes Photon Lord, and The Zombie Vampire. Link wise we carry 2 copies of Linkuriboh since it is a Kuriboh monster which makes it a target for funny Kuribohrn plays, 1 Knightmare Phoenix for backrow removal, 2 I:P Masquerena since it's one of the best link 2s in the game, 1 Dharc the Dark Charmer, Gloomy because Dark Monsters are incredibly common and Kuriboh, Linkuriboh and the Kuriboh Tokens are all Dark Monsters to make it, 1 S:P Little Knight because obvi, 1 Knightmare Unicorn because it's a great disruption with I:P on going second aside from going into S:P, Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax because it's a big boy to make into a towers, Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess for monster negates because it's a crazy monster and Underworld Goddess of the Closed World for board breaking going second or first with I:P that also makes it into a big scary towers that also locks disrupts the opponent's GY plays.

Main Combo Lines:

Kuriboh Engine - NS Kuriboh/Flute of Summoning Kuriboh SS Kuriboh>Multiply>2 Tokens for I:P>1 Token for Linkuriboh>1 Token for Linkuriboh>I:P and 2 Linkuribohs for Avramax/Apollousa>Linkuriboh GY effect to SS using final Token for cost.

Horus Engine - Imsety Hand Effect for King Sarc/Play King Sarc>King Sarc Dump Hapi>Continue Dumping for Duamutef and Qebehsenuef if you have further cards you want in the GY in your hand>SS All possible Horus Cards from GY>XYZ for Negates/Zombie Vampire. At 4 Horus, you can make 4 Material Apollousa/Link 2 I:P Masquerena and Link 2 Knightmare Phoenix for Avramax or leave Hapi and Imsety on board by using Duamutef and Qebehsenuef to Link 2 I:P for a disruption on the opponent's turn with either Underworld Goddess, S:P or Knightmare Unicorn.

Most Optimal possible combo going first - Imsety pitch a Horus for King's Sarc>King's Sarc another Horus for all Horus in GY>all Horus onto board>Link 4 Apollousa>Flute for Kuriboh to Board>Multiply>2 Tokens to I:P>2 Tokens for 2 Linkuribohs leaving your options open for either going to the opponent's turn and linking on the opponent's turn for Avramax/Underworld Goddess or just going in immediately on Avramax and using Linkuriboh GY effect on the final token.

Aside from the 20 slots used for the Multiply and Horus engines combined as well as the 9 cards in the deck required due to Maxx "C" existing, you can cut the Kuribohrn from the deck if you feel that you don't need to use the recursion for follow-up from its effect, leaving you with 28/29 cards in deck and allowing up to 12/11 cards for further non-engine. I went with more going second board breaker options myself, however your choice of non-engine is entirely up to you.

deck_excerpt: Melffy Spright  / Ciudad de Panamá WCQ Regional 2nd Place
deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Ernesto Perez

Tournament: Ciudad de Panamá WCQ Regional – August 25th 2024

This is a Grandpa's Muto deck profile or as the boomer friends knows him, Solomon Muto.

This @sshole has access to every card possible as(s) a shopkeeper. While his deck isn't the best, he can annoy every newbie of the game by wasting  him over 30 turns of his life to finnaly summon (S)Exodia the forbidden one. That way he doesn't need to lose his coolness or overthink about how to play better a combo. He is just a boomer whose trying to win without much effort by abusing this winding condition of Exodia.

I've tried not to make it ULTIMATELY unfair, for example with 3 copies of "Messenger of Peace" or other cards with insane draw power. IMO "Cyber Valley" is not very good in this deck versus strong opponent's like Odion for example... but, it can be pretty useful versus weaker decks cause it acts like "Messenger of Peace" in a way.

You can always use cards from side deck for some different approach, but if you are a boomer you can just play the easy way. "Union carrier" can be pretty strong to pick 3 pieces of exodia in 1 turn. Extra deck can give you some solutions to toxic cards.

Many other players are using decks with many spell cards to summon EXODIA in one turn. But this is not fun at all. 

The more pieces you have in your hand, the less cards you can use/hold, be aware of this problem. That's why you might have to use less monsters and more spell/traps. Cards like "Black Garden" + "Cauldron of the Old Man" can make you feel more safe through the turns.

deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Jorge Dutzan

Tournament: Viña del Mar WCQ Regional – August 31st 2024

Placement: 2nd Place

O *Structure Deck: Machine Rebellion* foi lançado em 2006 e marcou um ponto significativo na evolução dos baralhos temáticos de Yu-Gi-Oh!. Esse deck foi projetado para jogadores que queriam explorar o poder das máquinas, oferecendo uma abordagem agressiva e estratégica, focada na dominação do campo de batalha através de monstros mecânicos robustos e cartas de suporte especialmente voltadas para essa tipologia.

 

O principal atrativo do deck era a presença de monstros máquinas poderosos, como o *Ancient Gear Golem*, uma das cartas de destaque. Ele representava a força bruta do arquétipo, com um ataque elevado e a habilidade de impedir o uso de armadilhas no momento do ataque. O deck era construído ao redor dessas máquinas, que combinavam força física com habilidades que desestabilizavam as defesas adversárias. Além disso, cartas como *Limiter Removal* podiam dobrar o poder de ataque das máquinas temporariamente, permitindo golpes devastadores e a possibilidade de encerrar duelos rapidamente.

 

Outro ponto forte do *Machine Rebellion* era sua sinergia interna. A combinação de cartas de suporte como *Heavy Mech Support Platform* e *Gearframe* oferecia proteção extra para as máquinas mais vulneráveis, prolongando sua presença no campo. Isso possibilitava que os jogadores construíssem estratégias mais elaboradas e aumentassem suas chances de vitória.

 

Em termos de jogabilidade, o *Structure Deck: Machine Rebellion* trouxe uma mudança em como os duelos podiam ser abordados. Ele oferecia aos duelistas a oportunidade de construir um estilo de jogo focado em controle do campo através de força bruta e suporte técnico, destacando o poder dos monstros de máquina em um contexto competitivo.

 

Além disso, o deck fez sucesso não só por sua mecânica de jogo, mas também por seu design temático. O conceito de um exército de máquinas rebeldes, com um líder poderoso como o *Ancient Gear Golem*, evocava a ideia de uma revolução tecnológica nos duelos, o que cativou a imaginação de muitos jogadores.

 

Assim, o *Structure Deck: Machine Rebellion* de 2006 se consolidou como uma escolha popular entre os duelistas, tanto para iniciantes que queriam um deck competitivo pronto para uso, quanto para veteranos que buscavam novas formas de explorar a sinergia das cartas de máquina. Ele não só introduziu novos arquétipos como também influenciou futuras expansões e estratégias, garantindo seu lugar na história do jogo Yu-Gi-Oh!.
